intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-aminobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3PO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"inorganic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10NO7P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-oxo-5-(phosphonooxy)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b3-L-glutamyl phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8NO3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-aminopentanenitrile-2-oxoacid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid (proline aminonitrile precursor)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite surface and hydrogenated via surface-bound hydride transfer. The [Fe\u2084S\u2084] cluster analog of greigite facilitates two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 to formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally at hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This mimics the initial step of the acetyl-CoA pathway. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable at alkaline vent pH gradients (Lane & Martin, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction, subseafloor hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbs onto magnetite surface via carboxylate coordination. Molecular H\u2082 dissociates on the iron-oxide surface, and stepwise hydrogenation reduces formate to formaldehyde with water loss.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite-catalyzed Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C1 oxygenates from formate has been reported (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Formaldehyde is a key C1 building block in prebiotic chemistry. While formaldehyde is somewhat unstable under hydrothermal conditions, continuous generation and rapid reaction with other species maintains a steady-state flux (Cleaves, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite composite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"native iron may participate, pH 8-10, requires 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 stoichiometry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO\u2082 reductions yield formate \u2192 acetate (via acetyl-thioester intermediate on FeS) \u2192 pyruvate through reductive carboxylation. The reaction proceeds through C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 chain elongation on greigite surfaces, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 under hydrothermal conditions on Fe-Ni-S minerals has been demonstrated (Cody et al., 2000, 2004). Varma et al. (2018) showed native iron and Ni-Fe alloys catalyze CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate at 100\u00b0C under 1-50 bar. Pyruvate is a central hub in both prebiotic and extant metabolism (Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + Fe\u2070\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"proceeds via oxaloacetate and succinate intermediates (partial rTCA), pH 7-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes reductive carboxylation to oxaloacetate, which is reduced to malate, dehydrated to fumarate, reduced to succinate, and then carboxylated/reduced to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This represents a partial reductive tricarboxylic acid (rTCA) cycle analog on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 in water at 100\u00b0C drives the non-enzymatic formation of the core rTCA cycle intermediates from pyruvate through to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Keller et al. (2014) showed that simple iron-sulfur minerals catalyze rTCA-like transformations. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate is the direct biosynthetic precursor to glutamate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to L-glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083 from vent fluids, pH 8-10, reducing H\u2082-rich environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. This imine is then reduced by surface-bound hydride (H\u207b) from FeS-mediated H\u2082 activation, yielding L-glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been demonstrated (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). Wang et al. (2005) showed that iron-sulfur minerals catalyze reductive amination. This mirrors the biological transamination/glutamate dehydrogenase reaction that is central to nitrogen assimilation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate-high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"selective \u03b3-carboxylate reduction, reducing hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxylate group of glutamate is activated by surface coordination to FeS, enabling selective reduction to the semialdehyde. FeS acts as an electron donor and H\u2082 provides reducing equivalents. The product glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA) retains the \u03b1-amino acid moiety.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Selective carboxylate reduction to aldehyde on mineral surfaces is prebiotically plausible, as FeS can act as a strong reductant (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). In biology, this step requires ATP activation (\u03b3-glutamyl kinase) followed by NADPH reduction; the prebiotic analog uses mineral-surface activation and H\u2082 as reductant. Barge et al. (2019) showed that iron oxyhydroxide minerals can mediate selective reductions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"any\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required - spontaneous\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intramolecular Schiff base formation, spontaneous in aqueous solution, pH-independent\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-5-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic addition to the \u03b4-aldehyde, forming a cyclic Schiff base (carbinolamine \u2192 imine with loss of water). The product \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is the thermodynamic product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and occurs spontaneously in aqueous solution without enzymatic catalysis (Adams & Frank, 1980). The equilibrium between GSA and P5C strongly favors P5C at physiological and prebiotic pH values (Mezl & Knox, 1976). This reaction is pH-independent and occurs rapidly, making it one of the most robust steps in the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of P5C to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082 as terminal reductant, mineral-surface imine reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond in P5C is reduced by surface-activated H\u2082 on greigite. The FeS cluster facilitates heterolytic H\u2082 cleavage and hydride transfer to the electrophilic carbon of the imine, yielding the saturated pyrrolidine ring of L-proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Iron-sulfur mineral-catalyzed imine reduction under hydrothermal conditions is well-supported (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998). In biology, this step is catalyzed by pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase (P5CR) using NADPH; the prebiotic analog uses FeS-mediated H\u2082 activation as the reductant. The thermodynamic driving force is significant under H\u2082-rich hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 / montmorillonite / borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions pH 10-12, borate stabilizes intermediates, evaporitic pool setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The reaction proceeds via umpolung: one formaldehyde is activated to a glycolaldehyde enediol by base, then attacks a second formaldehyde. Borate complexation stabilizes the glycolaldehyde product against further condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is one of the most established prebiotic sugar syntheses (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate stabilization of glycolaldehyde and other sugars has been demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). Montmorillonite clay enhances the reaction by concentrating formaldehyde on its surface (Ferris, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol condensation to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aldol condensation followed by reduction in evaporitic pool, mild base\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde acts as the nucleophile (via enolization) and attacks acetaldehyde in a crossed aldol condensation. The initial aldol product (4-hydroxy-2-oxobutanal) undergoes dehydration and tautomerization, followed by further reduction on the mineral surface to yield succinaldehyde (butanedial).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Crossed aldol condensations between simple aldehydes on clay mineral surfaces are prebiotically plausible (Weber, 2001). Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions has been documented (Nagendrappa, 2011). The conversion to succinaldehyde may involve multiple steps but is supported by the diverse aldehyde chemistry observed in formose-type reactions under surface conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular reductive cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to P5C analog\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite + stibnite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker-cyclization, sequential imine formation then cyanide addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a 4-aminobutanal intermediate, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline. HCN then adds to the cyclic imine in a Strecker-type addition to form 2-cyanopyrrolidine (proline aminonitrile precursor).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis on cyclic imines is a well-established prebiotic route to cyclic amino acids (Miller, 1957; Lerner et al., 1993). The formation of \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline from succinaldehyde and ammonia is facile, and the subsequent HCN addition to cyclic imines has been demonstrated experimentally. Proline is consistently found in Strecker-based and electric discharge prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Cleaves et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of proline aminonitrile to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite / UV on TiO\u2082\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acid/base-catalyzed nitrile hydrolysis, UV-assisted, wet-dry cycling may accelerate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of 2-cyanopyrrolidine undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide) then to the carboxylic acid (proline). UV-activated TiO\u2082 can generate reactive oxygen species that accelerate hydrolysis under anoxic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis under mild prebiotic conditions is well-established as the final step of the Strecker synthesis (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). UV photocatalysis on TiO\u2082 can accelerate hydrolysis (Cleaves et al., 2008). The reaction proceeds readily at surface temperatures over geological timescales, especially during wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker variant on \u03b1-keto acid, HCN as cyanide source, aqueous pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base). HCN then adds to the imine to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile, which undergoes hydrolysis to yield glutamate. This is the Strecker variant using a preformed keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis on \u03b1-keto acids is one of the most well-characterized prebiotic amino acid formation routes (Strecker, 1850; Miller & Orgel, 1974). \u03b1-Ketoglutarate transported from hydrothermal settings to surface pools would undergo facile Strecker conversion. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and catalyzes the condensation (Ferris, 2005). This provides a second, surface-based route to glutamate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate phosphorylation and reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"apatite / struvite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry heating phase of wet-dry cycle activates phosphorylation, evaporitic mineral crust\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"During the dry phase of a wet-dry cycle, the \u03b3-carboxylate of glutamate reacts with surface phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite) to form \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate. The phosphate group activates the carboxylate toward nucleophilic reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Phosphorylation of carboxylates by phosphate minerals during dry heating is prebiotically established (Pasek et al., 2013; Becker et al., 2019). Apatite and struvite can drive phosphorylation under dry conditions at 60-100\u00b0C. This mirrors the biological \u03b3-glutamyl kinase step. The reaction requires concentration via evaporation and moderate heat.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083) / molybdenite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082S as reductant in cyanosulfidic environment, re-wetting phase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The activated \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate undergoes reductive dephosphorylation. H\u2082S donates electrons via sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite), reducing the acyl-phosphate to the aldehyde (glutamate-5-semialdehyde) with release of phosphate and H\u2082O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of acyl-phosphates by sulfide is prebiotically plausible in cyanosulfidic environments (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017). H\u2082S is abundant at volcanic hot springs and can serve as a reductant. Sulfide mineral surfaces facilitate the electron transfer. This provides a surface-environment analog to the biological NADPH-dependent \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyclization of GSA to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (optional, spontaneous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"spontaneous intramolecular cyclization, enhanced by wet-dry cycling concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Identical to rxn_007 - spontaneous intramolecular Schiff base formation. The \u03b1-amino group attacks the \u03b4-aldehyde. Concentration during dry phase of wet-dry cycling accelerates the intramolecular reaction relative to intermolecular side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C occurs in any aqueous environment (Adams & Frank, 1980). Including this as a surface reaction shows the environmental interconnection: GSA produced via surface phosphorylation-reduction (rxn_014, rxn_015) cyclizes to P5C in surface pools, which can then be reduced to proline by multiple routes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic reduction of P5C to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (thermal/photochemical reductants)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing equivalents from organic donors (NADH analogs) or ferrous iron in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"P5C undergoes imine reduction using available prebiotic reductants. Fe\u00b2\u207a can serve as a one-electron reductant (in two sequential transfers), or organic hydride donors such as dihydropyridines (prebiotic NADH analogs) donate a hydride to the C=N double bond to yield L-proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic NADH analogs (dihydropyridines from niacin) have been shown to reduce imines and related substrates (Mayer et al., 2015; Itoh et al., 2004). Fe\u00b2\u207a as a reductant in prebiotic pools is well-established (Barge et al., 2019). This provides a biochemical-environment route from P5C to proline that does not require hydrothermal H\u2082 pressure. The reaction mirrors biological P5C reductase.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation, proceeds readily above 100\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation. The keto group facilitates CO\u2082 loss through a cyclic transition state. Pyrite surface coordination lowers the activation barrier. The product acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate under hydrothermal conditions has been well-documented (Cody et al., 2004; Cooper et al., 2011). The reaction occurs readily at temperatures above 100\u00b0C and is catalyzed by metal sulfide surfaces. Acetaldehyde serves as a key precursor for C4-C5 aldehyde synthesis via aldol reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine synthesis from glutamate via reductive amination\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"prebiotic transamination catalyst (pyridoxal analog)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"multi-step: glutamate \u2192 N-acetylglutamate \u2192 ornithine, or via \u03b3-semialdehyde + amine exchange\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate-5-semialdehyde (from rxn_006) undergoes transamination at the \u03b4-position using NH\u2083 or an amine donor. Alternatively, glutamate undergoes \u03b3-carboxylate reduction and subsequent reductive amination of the resulting aldehyde to yield the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ornithine biosynthesis from glutamate is a fundamental metabolic pathway (Caldovic & Tuchman, 2003). Prebiotically, transamination reactions using pyridoxal analogs have been demonstrated (Zabinski & Toney, 2001; Metzler et al., 1954). While multi-step, this pathway provides a plausible route to ornithine as a proline precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative cyclization of ornithine to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u00b3\u207a or Cu\u00b2\u207a (dissolved metal oxidants)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"oxidative deamination of \u03b4-amino group, UV may assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine is oxidatively deaminated by dissolved Fe\u00b3\u207a or Cu\u00b2\u207a ions (or UV-generated radicals) to yield the \u03b4-aldehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C with release of NH\u2083. This is the ornithine \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C conversion.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase and ornithine cyclodeaminase both convert ornithine to P5C in biology (Graupner & White, 2001). The non-enzymatic analog uses metal-ion-catalyzed oxidative deamination, which has precedent in prebiotic chemistry (Barge et al., 2019). Fe\u00b3\u207a is a competent oxidant under mildly oxidizing surface conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal aminoaldehyde cyclization to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reductive amination of one aldehyde, then intramolecular cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks one aldehyde group of succinaldehyde to form 4-aminobutanal. The primary amine then undergoes intramolecular condensation with the remaining aldehyde to form the cyclic imine \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline (1-pyrroline), with loss of water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reaction of dialdehydes with ammonia to form cyclic imines is well-known (Sch\u00f6pf, 1937). Succinaldehyde + ammonia gives \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline quantitatively. This is a classic route to pyrrolidine rings in prebiotic synthesis (Pizzarello & Weber, 2004). The subsequent carboxylation or cyanide addition yields P5C or proline precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Carboxylation of 4-aminobutanal cyclization product to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO\u2082-rich vent fluid, \u03b1-carboxylation of cyclic imine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic imine (\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline) undergoes carboxylation at the \u03b1-position adjacent to the imine nitrogen. CO\u2082 insertion into the C-H bond is facilitated by the mineral surface, yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) directly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO\u2082 fixation into activated C-H bonds adjacent to electron-withdrawing groups is prebiotically plausible under high CO\u2082 pressures in hydrothermal environments (Amend & Shock, 1998). While speculative, this carboxylation is thermodynamically favorable at the high pCO\u2082 of early Earth hydrothermal systems and provides an alternative route to P5C from simpler cyclic precursors.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete hydrothermal rTCA pathway to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal route from CO\u2082 through the reductive TCA cycle analog to pyruvate, then \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, GSA, P5C, and finally proline. All steps occur under hydrothermal vent conditions with iron-sulfur mineral catalysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 surface aldol \u2192 Strecker cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate and then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where it undergoes formose and aldol reactions to form glycolaldehyde, which combines with acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation) to yield succinaldehyde. Strecker cyclization with NH\u2083 and HCN gives proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker glutamate \u2192 phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate from hydrothermal vents is converted to glutamate via surface Strecker synthesis. Glutamate is phosphorylated on apatite during dry phase, reduced to GSA by H\u2082S, cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline in prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine cyclization pathway to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate (from any source) is converted to ornithine via biochemical reductive amination, then ornithine undergoes oxidative cyclization to P5C, which is reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct succinaldehyde-ammonia cyclization to proline (hydrothermal)\",\n      \"description\": \"Succinaldehyde (from surface aldol chemistry transported to vents, or formed hydrothermally) reacts with ammonia to form 4-aminobutanal, which cyclizes. The cyclic imine is then carboxylated by CO\u2082 to P5C and reduced to proline on greigite.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glutamate \u2192 surface phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 hydrothermal P5C reduction\",\n      \"description\": \"Cross-environment pathway: glutamate formed hydrothermally is phosphorylated at the surface, reduced to GSA, cyclizes to P5C, then returns to hydrothermal conditions for P5C reduction to proline on FeS minerals.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-cyclization from formaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal vents enters surface formose chemistry to make glycolaldehyde. Pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde. Aldol condensation gives succinaldehyde. Strecker cyclization with HCN and NH\u2083 yields proline aminonitrile, hydrolyzed to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 cyclic Strecker \u2192 proline (full C1-build)\",\n      \"description\": \"Starting purely from C1 units: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde, which through further aldol and condensation chemistry yields succinaldehyde. NH\u2083 and HCN Strecker cyclization produces proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-biochemical: rTCA to glutamate, ornithine route, biochemical reduction\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA generates \u03b1-KG, reductive amination gives glutamate, biochemical processing yields ornithine, ornithine cyclizes to P5C, and biochemical reductants (prebiotic NADH analogs) reduce P5C to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface glutamate Strecker \u2192 hydrothermal GSA reduction \u2192 spontaneous P5C \u2192 biochemical proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Three-environment pathway: \u03b1-KG from hydrothermal vents undergoes surface Strecker synthesis to glutamate. Glutamate returns to hydrothermal vents for reduction to GSA. GSA cyclizes to P5C spontaneously. P5C is reduced to proline in biochemical prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - C1 hub molecule formed by hydrothermal formate reduction, feeds into formose chemistry and aldol pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate - central metabolic hub formed by hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation, feeds into rTCA (\u2192 \u03b1-KG) and decarboxylation (\u2192 acetaldehyde)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate - key C5 keto acid hub, product of reductive carboxylation, precursor to glutamate via both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"L-Glutamate - amino acid hub, formed by two independent routes (hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker), feeds into GSA/P5C pathway and ornithine pathway\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) - the master convergence point, immediate precursor to proline. Receives input from five distinct routes: GSA cyclization (hydrothermal and surface), ornithine oxidation, succinaldehyde carboxylation, and is reduced to proline by three routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "L-Proline is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network centered on five hub molecules: formaldehyde, pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, L-glutamate, and \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals generates C1\u2013C3 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate). These feed into reductive carboxylation to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate, which undergoes reductive amination to glutamate. Glutamate is transformed to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA), which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C\u2014the universal penultimate precursor to proline. Surface chemistry provides alternative routes via Strecker synthesis, HCN oligomerization, formose-derived aldehydes, and cyanosulfidic photochemistry. Ornithine-mediated cyclization and direct aldehyde-amine cyclizations offer additional convergent paths. Final reduction of P5C to proline occurs in hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical settings, yielding ten distinct pathways spanning all three environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)9/h2,5H,1,3H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H9NO", "iupac_name": "4-aminobutanal", "common_name": "4-aminobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "inorganic phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H10NO7P", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxo-5-(phosphonooxy)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "\u03b3-L-glutamyl phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H8NO3-", "iupac_name": "5-aminopentanenitrile-2-oxoacid", "common_name": "2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid (proline aminonitrile precursor)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite surface and hydrogenated via surface-bound hydride transfer. The [Fe\u2084S\u2084] cluster analog of greigite facilitates two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 to formate.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally at hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This mimics the initial step of the acetyl-CoA pathway. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable at alkaline vent pH gradients (Lane & Martin, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-450K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction, subseafloor hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbs onto magnetite surface via carboxylate coordination. Molecular H\u2082 dissociates on the iron-oxide surface, and stepwise hydrogenation reduces formate to formaldehyde with water loss.", "reasoning": "Magnetite-catalyzed Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C1 oxygenates from formate has been reported (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Formaldehyde is a key C1 building block in prebiotic chemistry. While formaldehyde is somewhat unstable under hydrothermal conditions, continuous generation and rapid reaction with other species maintains a steady-state flux (Cleaves, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite composite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "native iron may participate, pH 8-10, requires 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 stoichiometry"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO\u2082 reductions yield formate \u2192 acetate (via acetyl-thioester intermediate on FeS) \u2192 pyruvate through reductive carboxylation. The reaction proceeds through C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 chain elongation on greigite surfaces, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 under hydrothermal conditions on Fe-Ni-S minerals has been demonstrated (Cody et al., 2000, 2004). Varma et al. (2018) showed native iron and Ni-Fe alloys catalyze CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate at 100\u00b0C under 1-50 bar. Pyruvate is a central hub in both prebiotic and extant metabolism (Muchowska et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite + Fe\u2070", "aqueous": "true", "other": "proceeds via oxaloacetate and succinate intermediates (partial rTCA), pH 7-9"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes reductive carboxylation to oxaloacetate, which is reduced to malate, dehydrated to fumarate, reduced to succinate, and then carboxylated/reduced to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This represents a partial reductive tricarboxylic acid (rTCA) cycle analog on mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 in water at 100\u00b0C drives the non-enzymatic formation of the core rTCA cycle intermediates from pyruvate through to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Keller et al. (2014) showed that simple iron-sulfur minerals catalyze rTCA-like transformations. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate is the direct biosynthetic precursor to glutamate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to L-glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/FeS", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH\u2083 from vent fluids, pH 8-10, reducing H\u2082-rich environment"}, "mechanism": "NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. This imine is then reduced by surface-bound hydride (H\u207b) from FeS-mediated H\u2082 activation, yielding L-glutamate.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been demonstrated (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). Wang et al. (2005) showed that iron-sulfur minerals catalyze reductive amination. This mirrors the biological transamination/glutamate dehydrogenase reaction that is central to nitrogen assimilation."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate-high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "selective \u03b3-carboxylate reduction, reducing hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxylate group of glutamate is activated by surface coordination to FeS, enabling selective reduction to the semialdehyde. FeS acts as an electron donor and H\u2082 provides reducing equivalents. The product glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA) retains the \u03b1-amino acid moiety.", "reasoning": "Selective carboxylate reduction to aldehyde on mineral surfaces is prebiotically plausible, as FeS can act as a strong reductant (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). In biology, this step requires ATP activation (\u03b3-glutamyl kinase) followed by NADPH reduction; the prebiotic analog uses mineral-surface activation and H\u2082 as reductant. Barge et al. (2019) showed that iron oxyhydroxide minerals can mediate selective reductions."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-400K", "pressure": "any", "catalyst": "none required - spontaneous", "aqueous": "true", "other": "intramolecular Schiff base formation, spontaneous in aqueous solution, pH-independent"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-5-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic addition to the \u03b4-aldehyde, forming a cyclic Schiff base (carbinolamine \u2192 imine with loss of water). The product \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is the thermodynamic product.", "reasoning": "This cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and occurs spontaneously in aqueous solution without enzymatic catalysis (Adams & Frank, 1980). The equilibrium between GSA and P5C strongly favors P5C at physiological and prebiotic pH values (Mezl & Knox, 1976). This reaction is pH-independent and occurs rapidly, making it one of the most robust steps in the network."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of P5C to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H\u2082 as terminal reductant, mineral-surface imine reduction"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond in P5C is reduced by surface-activated H\u2082 on greigite. The FeS cluster facilitates heterolytic H\u2082 cleavage and hydride transfer to the electrophilic carbon of the imine, yielding the saturated pyrrolidine ring of L-proline.", "reasoning": "Iron-sulfur mineral-catalyzed imine reduction under hydrothermal conditions is well-supported (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998). In biology, this step is catalyzed by pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase (P5CR) using NADPH; the prebiotic analog uses FeS-mediated H\u2082 activation as the reductant. The thermodynamic driving force is significant under H\u2082-rich hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 / montmorillonite / borate", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline conditions pH 10-12, borate stabilizes intermediates, evaporitic pool setting"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The reaction proceeds via umpolung: one formaldehyde is activated to a glycolaldehyde enediol by base, then attacks a second formaldehyde. Borate complexation stabilizes the glycolaldehyde product against further condensation.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is one of the most established prebiotic sugar syntheses (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate stabilization of glycolaldehyde and other sugars has been demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). Montmorillonite clay enhances the reaction by concentrating formaldehyde on its surface (Ferris, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface aldol condensation to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aldol condensation followed by reduction in evaporitic pool, mild base"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde acts as the nucleophile (via enolization) and attacks acetaldehyde in a crossed aldol condensation. The initial aldol product (4-hydroxy-2-oxobutanal) undergoes dehydration and tautomerization, followed by further reduction on the mineral surface to yield succinaldehyde (butanedial).", "reasoning": "Crossed aldol condensations between simple aldehydes on clay mineral surfaces are prebiotically plausible (Weber, 2001). Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions has been documented (Nagendrappa, 2011). The conversion to succinaldehyde may involve multiple steps but is supported by the diverse aldehyde chemistry observed in formose-type reactions under surface conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Intramolecular reductive cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to P5C analog", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite + stibnite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Strecker-cyclization, sequential imine formation then cyanide addition"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a 4-aminobutanal intermediate, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline. HCN then adds to the cyclic imine in a Strecker-type addition to form 2-cyanopyrrolidine (proline aminonitrile precursor).", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis on cyclic imines is a well-established prebiotic route to cyclic amino acids (Miller, 1957; Lerner et al., 1993). The formation of \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline from succinaldehyde and ammonia is facile, and the subsequent HCN addition to cyclic imines has been demonstrated experimentally. Proline is consistently found in Strecker-based and electric discharge prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Cleaves et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of proline aminonitrile to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite / UV on TiO\u2082", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acid/base-catalyzed nitrile hydrolysis, UV-assisted, wet-dry cycling may accelerate"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of 2-cyanopyrrolidine undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide) then to the carboxylic acid (proline). UV-activated TiO\u2082 can generate reactive oxygen species that accelerate hydrolysis under anoxic conditions.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis under mild prebiotic conditions is well-established as the final step of the Strecker synthesis (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). UV photocatalysis on TiO\u2082 can accelerate hydrolysis (Cleaves et al., 2008). The reaction proceeds readily at surface temperatures over geological timescales, especially during wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Strecker variant on \u03b1-keto acid, HCN as cyanide source, aqueous pool"}, "mechanism": "NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base). HCN then adds to the imine to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile, which undergoes hydrolysis to yield glutamate. This is the Strecker variant using a preformed keto acid.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis on \u03b1-keto acids is one of the most well-characterized prebiotic amino acid formation routes (Strecker, 1850; Miller & Orgel, 1974). \u03b1-Ketoglutarate transported from hydrothermal settings to surface pools would undergo facile Strecker conversion. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and catalyzes the condensation (Ferris, 2005). This provides a second, surface-based route to glutamate."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Glutamate phosphorylation and reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "apatite / struvite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry heating phase of wet-dry cycle activates phosphorylation, evaporitic mineral crust"}, "mechanism": "During the dry phase of a wet-dry cycle, the \u03b3-carboxylate of glutamate reacts with surface phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite) to form \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate. The phosphate group activates the carboxylate toward nucleophilic reduction.", "reasoning": "Phosphorylation of carboxylates by phosphate minerals during dry heating is prebiotically established (Pasek et al., 2013; Becker et al., 2019). Apatite and struvite can drive phosphorylation under dry conditions at 60-100\u00b0C. This mirrors the biological \u03b3-glutamyl kinase step. The reaction requires concentration via evaporation and moderate heat."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083) / molybdenite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H\u2082S as reductant in cyanosulfidic environment, re-wetting phase"}, "mechanism": "The activated \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate undergoes reductive dephosphorylation. H\u2082S donates electrons via sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite), reducing the acyl-phosphate to the aldehyde (glutamate-5-semialdehyde) with release of phosphate and H\u2082O.", "reasoning": "Reduction of acyl-phosphates by sulfide is prebiotically plausible in cyanosulfidic environments (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017). H\u2082S is abundant at volcanic hot springs and can serve as a reductant. Sulfide mineral surfaces facilitate the electron transfer. This provides a surface-environment analog to the biological NADPH-dependent \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase step."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Surface cyclization of GSA to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (optional, spontaneous)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "spontaneous intramolecular cyclization, enhanced by wet-dry cycling concentration"}, "mechanism": "Identical to rxn_007 - spontaneous intramolecular Schiff base formation. The \u03b1-amino group attacks the \u03b4-aldehyde. Concentration during dry phase of wet-dry cycling accelerates the intramolecular reaction relative to intermolecular side reactions.", "reasoning": "Spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C occurs in any aqueous environment (Adams & Frank, 1980). Including this as a surface reaction shows the environmental interconnection: GSA produced via surface phosphorylation-reduction (rxn_014, rxn_015) cyclizes to P5C in surface pools, which can then be reduced to proline by multiple routes."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic reduction of P5C to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (thermal/photochemical reductants)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing equivalents from organic donors (NADH analogs) or ferrous iron in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "P5C undergoes imine reduction using available prebiotic reductants. Fe\u00b2\u207a can serve as a one-electron reductant (in two sequential transfers), or organic hydride donors such as dihydropyridines (prebiotic NADH analogs) donate a hydride to the C=N double bond to yield L-proline.", "reasoning": "Prebiotic NADH analogs (dihydropyridines from niacin) have been shown to reduce imines and related substrates (Mayer et al., 2015; Itoh et al., 2004). Fe\u00b2\u207a as a reductant in prebiotic pools is well-established (Barge et al., 2019). This provides a biochemical-environment route from P5C to proline that does not require hydrothermal H\u2082 pressure. The reaction mirrors biological P5C reductase."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Hydrothermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation, proceeds readily above 100\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation. The keto group facilitates CO\u2082 loss through a cyclic transition state. Pyrite surface coordination lowers the activation barrier. The product acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate under hydrothermal conditions has been well-documented (Cody et al., 2004; Cooper et al., 2011). The reaction occurs readily at temperatures above 100\u00b0C and is catalyzed by metal sulfide surfaces. Acetaldehyde serves as a key precursor for C4-C5 aldehyde synthesis via aldol reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Ornithine synthesis from glutamate via reductive amination", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "prebiotic transamination catalyst (pyridoxal analog)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "multi-step: glutamate \u2192 N-acetylglutamate \u2192 ornithine, or via \u03b3-semialdehyde + amine exchange"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde (from rxn_006) undergoes transamination at the \u03b4-position using NH\u2083 or an amine donor. Alternatively, glutamate undergoes \u03b3-carboxylate reduction and subsequent reductive amination of the resulting aldehyde to yield the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine.", "reasoning": "Ornithine biosynthesis from glutamate is a fundamental metabolic pathway (Caldovic & Tuchman, 2003). Prebiotically, transamination reactions using pyridoxal analogs have been demonstrated (Zabinski & Toney, 2001; Metzler et al., 1954). While multi-step, this pathway provides a plausible route to ornithine as a proline precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Oxidative cyclization of ornithine to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe\u00b3\u207a or Cu\u00b2\u207a (dissolved metal oxidants)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "oxidative deamination of \u03b4-amino group, UV may assist"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine is oxidatively deaminated by dissolved Fe\u00b3\u207a or Cu\u00b2\u207a ions (or UV-generated radicals) to yield the \u03b4-aldehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C with release of NH\u2083. This is the ornithine \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C conversion.", "reasoning": "Ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase and ornithine cyclodeaminase both convert ornithine to P5C in biology (Graupner & White, 2001). The non-enzymatic analog uses metal-ion-catalyzed oxidative deamination, which has precedent in prebiotic chemistry (Barge et al., 2019). Fe\u00b3\u207a is a competent oxidant under mildly oxidizing surface conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Direct hydrothermal aminoaldehyde cyclization to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reductive amination of one aldehyde, then intramolecular cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks one aldehyde group of succinaldehyde to form 4-aminobutanal. The primary amine then undergoes intramolecular condensation with the remaining aldehyde to form the cyclic imine \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline (1-pyrroline), with loss of water.", "reasoning": "The reaction of dialdehydes with ammonia to form cyclic imines is well-known (Sch\u00f6pf, 1937). Succinaldehyde + ammonia gives \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline quantitatively. This is a classic route to pyrrolidine rings in prebiotic synthesis (Pizzarello & Weber, 2004). The subsequent carboxylation or cyanide addition yields P5C or proline precursors."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Carboxylation of 4-aminobutanal cyclization product to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO\u2082-rich vent fluid, \u03b1-carboxylation of cyclic imine"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic imine (\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline) undergoes carboxylation at the \u03b1-position adjacent to the imine nitrogen. CO\u2082 insertion into the C-H bond is facilitated by the mineral surface, yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) directly.", "reasoning": "CO\u2082 fixation into activated C-H bonds adjacent to electron-withdrawing groups is prebiotically plausible under high CO\u2082 pressures in hydrothermal environments (Amend & Shock, 1998). While speculative, this carboxylation is thermodynamically favorable at the high pCO\u2082 of early Earth hydrothermal systems and provides an alternative route to P5C from simpler cyclic precursors."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Complete hydrothermal rTCA pathway to proline", "description": "Full hydrothermal route from CO\u2082 through the reductive TCA cycle analog to pyruvate, then \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, GSA, P5C, and finally proline. All steps occur under hydrothermal vent conditions with iron-sulfur mineral catalysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 surface aldol \u2192 Strecker cyclization", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate and then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where it undergoes formose and aldol reactions to form glycolaldehyde, which combines with acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation) to yield succinaldehyde. Strecker cyclization with NH\u2083 and HCN gives proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_003", "rxn_018", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_005", "mol_015", "mol_009", "mol_020", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Surface Strecker glutamate \u2192 phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate from hydrothermal vents is converted to glutamate via surface Strecker synthesis. Glutamate is phosphorylated on apatite during dry phase, reduced to GSA by H\u2082S, cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline in prebiotic pools.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_019", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Ornithine cyclization pathway to proline", "description": "Glutamate (from any source) is converted to ornithine via biochemical reductive amination, then ornithine undergoes oxidative cyclization to P5C, which is reduced to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_016", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Direct succinaldehyde-ammonia cyclization to proline (hydrothermal)", "description": "Succinaldehyde (from surface aldol chemistry transported to vents, or formed hydrothermally) reacts with ammonia to form 4-aminobutanal, which cyclizes. The cyclic imine is then carboxylated by CO\u2082 to P5C and reduced to proline on greigite.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_017", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal glutamate \u2192 surface phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 hydrothermal P5C reduction", "description": "Cross-environment pathway: glutamate formed hydrothermally is phosphorylated at the surface, reduced to GSA, cyclizes to P5C, then returns to hydrothermal conditions for P5C reduction to proline on FeS minerals.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_019", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Surface Strecker-cyclization from formaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal vents enters surface formose chemistry to make glycolaldehyde. Pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde. Aldol condensation gives succinaldehyde. Strecker cyclization with HCN and NH\u2083 yields proline aminonitrile, hydrolyzed to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_018", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_015", "mol_009", "mol_020", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 cyclic Strecker \u2192 proline (full C1-build)", "description": "Starting purely from C1 units: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde, which through further aldol and condensation chemistry yields succinaldehyde. NH\u2083 and HCN Strecker cyclization produces proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_005", "mol_015", "mol_020", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Mixed hydrothermal-biochemical: rTCA to glutamate, ornithine route, biochemical reduction", "description": "Hydrothermal rTCA generates \u03b1-KG, reductive amination gives glutamate, biochemical processing yields ornithine, ornithine cyclizes to P5C, and biochemical reductants (prebiotic NADH analogs) reduce P5C to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_016", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Surface glutamate Strecker \u2192 hydrothermal GSA reduction \u2192 spontaneous P5C \u2192 biochemical proline", "description": "Three-environment pathway: \u03b1-KG from hydrothermal vents undergoes surface Strecker synthesis to glutamate. Glutamate returns to hydrothermal vents for reduction to GSA. GSA cyclizes to P5C spontaneously. P5C is reduced to proline in biochemical prebiotic pools.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "description": "Formaldehyde - C1 hub molecule formed by hydrothermal formate reduction, feeds into formose chemistry and aldol pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Pyruvate - central metabolic hub formed by hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation, feeds into rTCA (\u2192 \u03b1-KG) and decarboxylation (\u2192 acetaldehyde)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate - key C5 keto acid hub, product of reductive carboxylation, precursor to glutamate via both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "L-Glutamate - amino acid hub, formed by two independent routes (hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker), feeds into GSA/P5C pathway and ornithine pathway", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_014", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) - the master convergence point, immediate precursor to proline. Receives input from five distinct routes: GSA cyclization (hydrothermal and surface), ornithine oxidation, succinaldehyde carboxylation, and is reduced to proline by three routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_016", "rxn_020", "rxn_022"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_017"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 468572.4809169769, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T10:14:15.918175", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Proline\nOVERALL STRATEGY: L-Proline is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network centered on five hub molecules: formaldehyde, pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, L-glutamate, and \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals generates C1\u2013C3 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate). These feed into reductive carboxylation to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate, which undergoes reductive amination to glutamate. Glutamate is transformed to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA), which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C\u2014the universal penultimate precursor to proline. Surface chemistry provides alternative routes via Strecker synthesis, HCN oligomerization, formose-derived aldehydes, and cyanosulfidic photochemistry. Ornithine-mediated cyclization and direct aldehyde-amine cyclizations offer additional convergent paths. Final reduction of P5C to proline occurs in hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical settings, yielding ten distinct pathways spanning all three environments.\n\nMOLECULES (22 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [starting]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CHO2- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C5H6O5 (\u03b1-ketoglutarate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C5H9NO4 (L-glutamate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C5H9NO3 (L-glutamate-5-semialdehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C5H7NO2 (\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C5H9NO2 (L-proline) [target]\n  - mol_015: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H12N2O2 (L-ornithine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C4H9NO (4-aminobutyraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: H3PO4 (inorganic phosphate) [starting]\n  - mol_019: C5H10NO7P (\u03b3-L-glutamyl phosphate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_020: C4H6O2 (succinaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_022: C5H8NO3- (2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid (proline aminonitrile precursor)) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (22 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_005, mol_006 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_008, mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_010 (Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_010, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_011 (Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to L-glutamate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_011, mol_002 -> mol_012 (Reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_012 -> mol_013, mol_006 (Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_008: mol_013, mol_002 -> mol_014 (Hydrothermal reduction of P5C to L-proline) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_009: mol_005, mol_005 -> mol_015 (Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_009, mol_015 -> mol_020 (Surface aldol condensation to succinaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_020, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_022 (Intramolecular reductive cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to P5C analog) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_022, mol_006 -> mol_014 (Hydrolysis of proline aminonitrile to L-proline) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_010, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_011 (Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_011, mol_018 -> mol_019 (Glutamate phosphorylation and reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_019, mol_021 -> mol_012 (Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_012 -> mol_013, mol_006 (Surface cyclization of GSA to P5C) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017: mol_013 -> mol_014 (Biochemical/prebiotic reduction of P5C to L-proline) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_018: mol_008 -> mol_009, mol_001 (Hydrothermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_019: mol_011, mol_003 -> mol_016 (Ornithine synthesis from glutamate via reductive amination) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_020: mol_016 -> mol_013, mol_003 (Oxidative cyclization of ornithine to P5C) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_021: mol_020, mol_003 -> mol_017 (Direct hydrothermal aminoaldehyde cyclization to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_022: mol_017, mol_001 -> mol_013 (Carboxylation of 4-aminobutanal cyclization product to P5C) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Complete hydrothermal rTCA pathway to proline (6 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 surface aldol \u2192 Strecker cyclization (8 steps)\n  - P3: Surface Strecker glutamate \u2192 phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline (6 steps)\n  - P4: Ornithine cyclization pathway to proline (4 steps)\n  - P5: Direct succinaldehyde-ammonia cyclization to proline (hydrothermal) (3 steps)\n  - P6: Hydrothermal glutamate \u2192 surface phosphorylation \u2192 GSA \u2192 hydrothermal P5C reduction (7 steps)\n  - P7: Surface Strecker-cyclization from formaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde (6 steps)\n  - P8: Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 cyclic Strecker \u2192 proline (full C1-build) (6 steps)\n  - P9: Mixed hydrothermal-biochemical: rTCA to glutamate, ornithine route, biochemical reduction (6 steps)\n  - P10: Surface glutamate Strecker \u2192 hydrothermal GSA reduction \u2192 spontaneous P5C \u2192 biochemical proline (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLEC