u2192P5C cyclization is well-established and provides a strong thermodynamic driving force. No mineral agents explicitly named.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Break rxn_004 into explicit rTCA half-cycle steps (oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, succinate, succinyl intermediate) with specific mineral catalysts\",\n        \"Specify FeS or NiS mineral catalysts for rxn_006 and cite experimental precedent for selective carboxylate-to-aldehyde reduction\",\n        \"Consider thioester-mediated activation as alternative to direct reduction in rxn_006\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.76,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"Good hydrothermal\u2192surface environmental flow. CO\u2082 to formate is very well established. The pathway is convergent, requiring both formaldehyde-derived glycolaldehyde and pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde to meet at rxn_010. The aldol condensation (rxn_010) forming succinaldehyde from acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde is plausible but product selectivity is poor under prebiotic conditions. The Strecker-type cyclization (rxn_011) to form the aminonitrile is creative but the intramolecular cyclization specificity needs justification. Acetaldehyde source from pyruvate decarboxylation should be made explicit in pathway description.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify mineral catalyst for aldol condensation (e.g., borate, hydrotalcite)\",\n        \"Provide evidence or mechanism for regioselective Strecker cyclization in rxn_011\",\n        \"Clarify that acetaldehyde comes from rxn_003\u2192rxn_018 as convergent input\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.62,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"The phosphorylation of glutamate (rxn_014) without ATP or polyphosphate activation is the critical weakness. This step borrows from modern biochemistry (glutamate kinase) without establishing a plausible prebiotic phosphorylation mechanism. Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate by H\u2082S (rxn_015) is speculative\u2014thiol-mediated reductions exist but this specific transformation lacks experimental precedent. The pathway also implicitly requires \u03b1-KG from hydrothermal sources but doesn't explicitly include those steps. Strecker synthesis of glutamate (rxn_013) using HCN is reasonable.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace inorganic phosphate with polyphosphate or use mineral-assisted phosphorylation (e.g., schreibersite)\",\n        \"Consider trimetaphosphate as phosphorylating agent\",\n        \"Provide literature support for thiol-mediated reduction of acyl phosphate to aldehyde\",\n        \"Include explicit \u03b1-KG source in pathway\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.55,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.60,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.70,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.60,\n      \"feedback\": \"Ornithine synthesis from glutamate (rxn_019) is a multistep process even biochemically (requires N-acetylation, phosphorylation, reduction, transamination, deacetylation). Representing it as a single reductive amination is a significant oversimplification\u2014the \u03b4-amino group installation on glutamate requires activation of the \u03b4-carboxylate. Oxidative cyclization of ornithine (rxn_020) requires a suitable oxidant in a prebiotic biochemical setting. The pathway is too reliant on modern biochemical logic without prebiotic justification.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Break ornithine synthesis into plausible prebiotic steps or provide alternative route\",\n        \"Specify the oxidant for ornithine cyclization (Cu\u00b2\u207a, pyrite?)\",\n        \"Consider whether ornithine is better treated as a starting material from meteoritic sources\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_022\": 0.40,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.75\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.52,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.58,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.62,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.58,\n      \"feedback\": \"Attractively short pathway but the carboxylation of the \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline to P5C (rxn_022) is the major weakness. Introducing a carboxylate at C2 of a cyclic imine under prebiotic conditions lacks clear mechanistic precedent. The reductive amination/cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia (rxn_021) is more plausible\u2014formation of cyclic imines from dialdehydes and amines is known. However, succinaldehyde itself needs to be sourced (from P2-type steps), which isn't included in the 3-step count.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Provide mechanistic detail for C2-carboxylation of pyrroline\",\n        \"Consider CO\u2082 insertion via radical mechanism or metal-carboxylation\",\n        \"Include succinaldehyde synthesis steps in pathway count\",\n        \"Alternatively, start from a C5 aldehyde already bearing the carboxylate\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.75\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.60,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.52,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway crosses between hydrothermal and surface environments and then returns to hydrothermal for the final reduction. The back-and-forth between environments is geologically awkward\u2014material transport from vents to surface and back is unlikely in a single reaction sequence. Combines weaknesses of P1 (rxn_004) and P3 (rxn_014, rxn_015). The phosphorylation step remains problematic.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Choose a single environment for GSA formation\u2014either hydrothermal reduction or surface phosphorylation, not both in one pathway\",\n        \"If return to hydrothermal is necessary, justify with geological scenario (e.g., tidal recycling)\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.72\n      },\