ons\": [\n        \"Clarify acetaldehyde source\u2014could it come from formaldehyde condensation instead of pyruvate decarboxylation?\",\n        \"Specify UV conditions for any photochemical steps on surface\",\n        \"Add mineral specifications for each surface reaction\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.70,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.66,\n      \"feedback\": \"Clean hydrothermal\u2192biochemical environmental flow is this pathway's strength. The ornithine steps (rxn_019, rxn_020) are the main liabilities\u2014ornithine synthesis from glutamate is biochemically complex and its prebiotic plausibility is weak. The concept of hydrothermal amino acid synthesis feeding into early enzymatic/ribozyme-catalyzed cyclization is sound in principle.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Provide evidence for prebiotic ornithine synthesis\",\n        \"Consider whether early peptide catalysts could mediate ornithine formation\",\n        \"Strengthen rxn_004 with mineral catalyst specification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.65,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"Compact pathway with good environmental flow (Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Biochemical). Surface Strecker for glutamate is reasonable. The glutamate reduction to GSA (rxn_006) in hydrothermal conditions remains the key challenge. Spontaneous P5C formation and biochemical reduction are solid. Needs explicit \u03b1-KG sourcing from hydrothermal reactions to be complete.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify reducing agent and mineral catalyst for rxn_006\",\n        \"Include \u03b1-KG production steps for completeness\",\n        \"Consider FeS-mediated carboxylate reduction mechanisms\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network for L-proline with excellent topological design. The identification of P5C as the universal penultimate precursor and the convergent design channeling five hub molecules through multiple pathways is a significant strength. The network demonstrates good environmental flow logic (hydrothermal C1/C3 building blocks \u2192 surface diversification \u2192 biochemical finishing). However, several critical reactions lack experimental support or detailed mechanistic justification: (1) the direct pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG transformation (rxn_004) compresses multiple rTCA steps; (2) selective glutamate C5 reduction to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic catalysis is poorly precedented; (3) phosphorylation without ATP/polyphosphate (rxn_014) is thermodynamically unfavorable; (4) ornithine synthesis (rxn_019) is oversimplified; (5) pyrroline carboxylation (rxn_022) lacks mechanistic support. Mineral catalysts are not specified for most hydrothermal and surface reactions\u2014this is a significant omission. No literature citations are provided for any reaction. The L- stereochemistry of proline is assumed throughout but no chiral induction mechanism is discussed. The network would benefit from: breaking multi-step compres