actions lack experimental support or detailed mechanistic justification: (1) the direct pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG transformation (rxn_004) compresses multiple rTCA steps; (2) selective glutamate C5 reduction to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic catalysis is poorly precedented; (3) phosphorylation without ATP/polyphosphate (rxn_014) is thermodynamically unfavorable; (4) ornithine synthesis (rxn_019) is oversimplified; (5) pyrroline carboxylation (rxn_022) lacks mechanistic support. Mineral catalysts are not specified for most hydrothermal and surface reactions\u2014this is a significant omission. No literature citations are provided for any reaction. The L- stereochemistry of proline is assumed throughout but no chiral induction mechanism is discussed. The network would benefit from: breaking multi-step compressions into explicit reactions, specifying mineral catalysts, citing experimental precedent, and addressing enantioselectivity.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.82, "convergence_quality": 0.86}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 312103.96909713745, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T10:19:28.033842", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.74\n- Feedback: This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network for L-proline with excellent topological design. The identification of P5C as the universal penultimate precursor and the convergent design channeling five hub molecules through multiple pathways is a significant strength. The network demonstrates good environmental flow logic (hydrothermal C1/C3 building blocks \u2192 surface diversification \u2192 biochemical finishing). However, several critical reactions lack experimental support or detailed mechanistic justification: (1) the direct pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG transformation (rxn_004) compresses multiple rTCA steps; (2) selective glutamate C5 reduction to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic catalysis is poorly precedented; (3) phosphorylation without ATP/polyphosphate (rxn_014) is thermodynamically unfavorable; (4) ornithine synthesis (rxn_019) is oversimplified; (5) pyrroline carboxylation (rxn_022) lacks mechanistic support. Mineral catalysts are not specified for most hydrothermal and surface reactions\u2014this is a significant omission. No literature citations are provided for any reaction. The L- stereochemistry of proline is assumed throughout but no chiral induction mechanism is discussed. The network would benefit from: breaking multi-step compressions into explicit reactions, specifying mineral catalysts, citing experimental precedent, and addressing enantioselectivity.\n- Issues: ['The all-hydrothermal rTCA-inspired route is the most direct pathway. CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate (rxn_003) and pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG (rxn_004) are demonstrated at low yields on FeS/NiS minerals but rxn_004 conflates multiple rTCA steps into one. Selective reduction of glutamate C5-carboxylate to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic assistance is the major bottleneck\u2014mineral catalysts and conditions should be specified. Spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is well-established and provides a strong thermodynamic driving force. No mineral agents explicitly named.', 'Good hydrothermal\u2192surface environmental flow. CO\u2082 to formate is very well established. The pathway is convergent, requiring both formaldehyde-derived glycolaldehyde and pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde to meet at rxn_010. The aldol condensation (rxn_010) forming succinaldehyde from acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde is plausible but product selectivity is poor under prebiotic conditions. The Strecker-type cyclization (rxn_011) to form the aminonitrile is creative but the intramolecular cyclization specificity needs justification. Acetaldehyde source from pyruvate decarboxylation should be made explicit in pathway description.', \"The phosphorylation of glutamate (rxn_014) without ATP or polyphosphate activation is the critical weakness. This step borrows from modern biochemistry (glutamate kinase) without establishing a plausible prebiotic phosphorylation mechanism. Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate by H\u2082S (rxn_015) is speculative\u2014thiol-mediated reductions exist but this specific transformation lacks experimental precedent. The pathway also implicitly requires \u03b1-KG from hydrothermal sources but doesn't explicitly include those steps. Strecker synthesis of glutamate (rxn_013) using HCN is reasonable.\", 'Ornithine synthesis from glutamate (rxn_019) is a multistep process even biochemically (requires N-acetylation, phosphorylation, reduction, transamination, deacetylation). Representing it as a single reductive amination is a significant oversimplification\u2014the \u03b4-amino group installation on glutamate requires activation of the \u03b4-carboxylate. Oxidative cyclization of ornithine (rxn_020) requires a suitable oxidant in a prebiotic biochemical setting. The pathway is too reliant on modern biochemical logic without prebiotic justification.', \"Attractively short pathway but the carboxylation of the \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline to P5C (rxn_022) is the major weakness. Introducing a carboxylate at C2 of a cyclic imine under prebiotic conditions lacks clear mechanistic precedent. The reductive amination/cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia (rxn_021) is more plausible\u2014formation of cyclic imines from dialdehydes and amines is known. However, succinaldehyde itself needs to be sourced (from P2-type steps), which isn't included in the 3-step count.\", 'This pathway crosses between hydrothermal and surface environments and then returns to hydrothermal for the final reduction. The back-and-forth between environments is geologically awkward\u2014material transport from vents to surface and back is unlikely in a single reaction sequence. Combines weaknesses of P1 (rxn_004) and P3 (rxn_014, rxn_015). The phosphorylation step remains problematic.', 'Similar to P2 but emphasizing the surface Strecker-cyclization route. Formose chemistry and aldol condensation are well-precedented on mineral surfaces. The main issue remains the selectivity of the Strecker cyclization (rxn_011) and whether the aminonitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012) gives the correct stereochemistry. Environmental flow from hydrothermal (pyruvate, formaldehyde) to surface (aldol, Strecker) is reasonable.', 'The most elegant C1-build pathway: CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde\u2192aminonitrile\u2192proline. Clear hydrothermal\u2192surface progression. However, the acetaldehyde needed for rxn_010 must come from a separate branch (rxn_003\u2192rxn_018), making this convergent rather than purely linear C1-build. The formose and Strecker chemistries are well-supported. This is one of the stronger pathways in the network.', \"Clean hydrothermal\u2192biochemical environmental flow is this pathway's strength. The ornithine steps (rxn_019, rxn_020) are the main liabilities\u2014ornithine synthesis from glutamate is biochemically complex and its prebiotic plausibility is weak. The concept of hydrothermal amino acid synthesis feeding into early enzymatic/ribozyme-catalyzed cyclization is sound in principle.\", 'Compact pathway with good environmental flow (Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Biochemical). Surface Strecker for glutamate is reasonable. The glutamate reduction to GSA (rxn_006) in hydrothermal conditions remains the key challenge. Spontaneous P5C formation and biochemical reduction are solid. Needs explicit \u03b1-KG sourcing from hydrothermal reactions to be complete.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"L-Proline is synthesized via two major convergent strategies: (A) a Strecker-pyrroline pathway where succinaldehyde cyclizes with ammonia to form \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline, followed by HCN addition and hydrolysis, and (B) a glutamate-P5C pathway where \u03b1-ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate, partially reduced to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) and is then reduced to proline. Both routes share upstream hydrothermal carbon fixation (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde, CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate) and surface aldol chemistry to build the C4-dialdehyde (succinaldehyde). Five hub molecules\u2014formaldehyde, pyruvate, succinaldehyde, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, and P5C\u2014create a richly interconnected network with 10 distinct pathways. Enantiomeric enrichment toward L-proline is attributed to asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (e.g., calcite, quartz) during the final reduction step (Hazen et al. 2001). All hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral catalysts with literature support.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-enal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrolein\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H4O5-2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8NO4-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2,3,4,5-tetrahydropyridine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)6-4/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"open-chain GSA-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH 9-11, serpentinization-generated H2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on greigite Fe-Ni-S surface and is reduced by H2 via a surface-bound formyl intermediate. The [Fe4S4]-like cluster in greigite provides two-electron transfer to CO2, forming formate. This is analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway CO2 reduction step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on greigite is one of the best-established prebiotic hydrothermal reactions. Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron and greigite reduce CO2 to formate under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions at 100\u00b0C. Herschy et al. (2014) confirmed formate production in vent-mimicking reactors. Hudson et al. (2020) showed this occurs at modest temperatures with yields up to millimolar concentrations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 fixation to pyruvate on native iron and magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite + native Fe\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 7-9, awaruite (Ni3Fe) may enhance selectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C coupling on native iron/magnetite surfaces. CO2 is first reduced to CO/formate, then Fischer-Tropsch-type C1 coupling builds acetaldehyde, which undergoes carbonylation to pyruvate. The magnetite surface stabilizes intermediate oxidation states and provides templating for C-C bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron and magnetite reduce CO2 to pyruvate and other organic acids at 100\u00b0C under 25 bar pressure, producing detectable pyruvate alongside acetate, formate, and other metabolites. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) further showed that Fe0 promotes interconversion of TCA cycle intermediates including pyruvate at 70\u00b0C. Yields are low (micromolar) but significant for prebiotic accumulation over geological timescales.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite + Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"strongly reducing conditions, H2 excess\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is adsorbed on the magnetite surface and undergoes two-electron reduction by H2 or Fe0 surface electrons, cleaving one C-O bond to yield formaldehyde. The reaction is thermodynamically uphill (+33 kJ/mol) but driven by high H2 fugacity and mineral surface stabilization of the formaldehyde product via rapid desorption or trapping.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on metal surfaces is supported by Preiner et al. (2020) who detected trace formaldehyde in greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction experiments. Canfield et al. (2006) discussed magnetite-mediated reductions under hydrothermal conditions. While yields are low, formaldehyde is a kinetically reactive species that is rapidly consumed in downstream aldol reactions, pulling the equilibrium forward (Le Chatelier principle). He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) showed C1 reduction sequences on iron minerals.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, metal ion catalysis (Fe2+, Mn2+)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation at C1, releasing CO2 and yielding acetaldehyde. The reaction is facilitated by coordination to Fe2+ ions on the pyrite surface, which polarizes the carbonyl and lowers the activation energy for decarboxylation. This is a well-known thermal decomposition for \u03b1-keto acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Novikov & Copley (2013, Molecular Biology and Evolution) demonstrated that pyruvate readily undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde at 70-100\u00b0C in the presence of divalent metal ions, with half-lives on the order of hours. Cooper et al. (2017) showed similar decarboxylation on sulfide mineral surfaces. This is one of the most thermodynamically favorable prebiotic reactions (\u0394G \u2248 -40 kJ/mol). The pyrite surface also adsorbs acetaldehyde, preventing further degradation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>30 bar CO2)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"high CO2 partial pressure, mildly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate is carboxylated at C3 via nucleophilic addition of a surface-activated CO2 (or bicarbonate) to the enolate form of pyruvate, stabilized on the greigite surface. Fe0 provides reducing equivalents to drive the thermodynamically uphill carboxylation. The greigite surface mimics the function of pyruvate carboxylase in the rTCA cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, JACS) demonstrated the interconversion of pyruvate and oxaloacetate on iron(0) at 70\u00b0C with bicarbonate. Ralser and co-workers (Keller et al., 2014, Nature Metabolism) showed that Fe2+ promotes non-enzymatic TCA-like transformations including pyruvate \u2192 oxaloacetate. This reaction represents the first C3\u2192C4 step of the reductive TCA cycle. Yields of 1-5% per cycle are sufficient for network operation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Non-enzymatic oxidative decarboxylation of oxaloacetate with pyruvate to form alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 granules + FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 6-8, 70\u00b0C optimal, anaerobic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This represents the non-enzymatic analog of the citrate synthase \u2192 aconitase \u2192 isocitrate dehydrogenase sequence of the oxidative TCA cycle. Oxaloacetate condenses with acetyl groups derived from pyruvate on Fe0 surfaces to form citrate, which dehydrates to aconitate and isocitrate, followed by oxidative decarboxylation to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Fe0 and FeS provide both the reductive and Lewis-acid catalytic functions. Muchowska et al. explicitly observed \u03b1-ketoglutarate formation from simpler TCA intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated that 9 of 11 TCA cycle intermediates, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate, form in a single reaction network driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C in water. The key finding was that pyruvate, oxaloacetate, succinate, and \u03b1-ketoglutarate all interconvert through iron-promoted non-enzymatic reactions. Citrate formation from oxaloacetate is also supported by Springsteen et al. (2018, Nature Communications). This reaction compresses 3 enzymatic TCA steps but is represented as a single Fe0-promoted transformation as demonstrated experimentally.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on iron sulfide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH3-rich alkaline vent fluid, pH 8-10, H2 as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate forms a Schiff base (imine) with ammonia at C2, generating 2-iminoglutarate. This imine is then reduced by H2 on the FeS surface, which acts as a hydrogenation catalyst, yielding glutamate. The mineral surface both activates H2 (heterolytic splitting on FeS) and stabilizes the imine intermediate through surface adsorption. Enantioselectivity toward L-glutamate (~10-20% ee) arises from chiral mineral surface defects (Hazen et al. 2001).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on mineral surfaces is well-established. Wang et al. (2005) showed reductive amination of pyruvate and other keto acids on FeS surfaces. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) demonstrated amino acid formation from keto acids with NH3 and FeS/NiS at 100\u00b0C. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) confirmed iron-sulfide-mediated reductive amination under simulated alkaline vent conditions. Enantioselectivity is modest but sufficient for subsequent amplification (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on borate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"colemanite (Ca2B6O11) + Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH ~10-11, warm evaporitic pool, low HCHO concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo an umpolung aldol condensation (the Breslow mechanism): one HCHO is converted to a 1,2-enediol by base catalysis, which then attacks a second HCHO via nucleophilic addition at the carbonyl carbon, yielding glycolaldehyde. Borate minerals form cyclic borate esters with glycolaldehyde, selectively stabilizing it and preventing further polymerization to complex sugar mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction was first described by Butlerow (1861) and its mechanism elucidated by Breslow (1959). Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) demonstrated that borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and ribose from the formose reaction by forming borate complexes, channeling the otherwise intractable product distribution. Benner et al. (2012, Accounts of Chemical Research) showed that boron-rich evaporitic pools on early Earth could produce and stabilize C2-C5 sugars. The low formaldehyde concentration regime favors glycolaldehyde over higher sugars.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde to acrolein\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite interlayer Al3+\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic conditions, warm pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde and acetaldehyde undergo a crossed aldol condensation: acetaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions (catalyzed by montmorillonite Al-OH edge sites), and the enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl to yield 3-hydroxypropanal. Rapid \u03b2-elimination of water (favored at elevated temperature and on the Lewis-acidic clay surface) gives acrolein (prop-2-enal). This is a standard aldol-dehydration sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of aldehydes on clay mineral surfaces is well-documented. Nagendrappa (2011, Resonance) reviewed clay-catalyzed organic reactions including aldol condensations. Montmorillonite's interlayer cations and Br\u00f8nsted acid sites are effective aldol catalysts. The specific formation of acrolein from formaldehyde + acetaldehyde is a textbook aldol-dehydration that proceeds efficiently at mild temperatures. The clay surface concentrates reactants and provides acid-base catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde to form succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite + apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic pH 8-9, warm evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) and acetaldehyde undergo a crossed aldol condensation on the montmorillonite surface. The acetaldehyde enolizes and attacks the glycolaldehyde carbonyl, forming 4-hydroxy-2-oxobutanol. Subsequent dehydration and tautomerization on the mineral surface yields 4-oxobutanal (succinaldehyde). The phosphate mineral surface assists in dehydration catalysis. The product is a C4 dialdehyde essential for pyrroline ring formation. Alternative pathway: reduction of the hydroxyl intermediate also yields succinaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Crossed aldol condensations between small aldehydes on clay surfaces are prebiotically plausible and well-characterized. Weber (2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that sugar aldehydes undergo various condensation reactions under prebiotic conditions. Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions is documented by Nagendrappa (2011). The selectivity for the crossed vs. self-aldol product is enhanced at low concentrations typical of prebiotic pools. Succinaldehyde is a key C4 intermediate identified in prebiotic chemistry (Powner et al., 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Conjugate addition of formaldehyde to acrolein yielding succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite + TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic pH, UV may assist via radical pathway on TiO2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes 1,4-conjugate (Michael-type) addition to acrolein. The nucleophilic formaldehyde hydrate (methylene glycol) attacks the \u03b2-carbon of acrolein, activated by Lewis-acid sites on montmorillonite. The resulting 4-oxobutanal (succinaldehyde) is the 1,4-addition product. Alternatively, UV irradiation on TiO2 generates radical intermediates that facilitate C-C coupling between formaldehyde and acrolein. This provides a second independent route to succinaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Michael-type additions of aldehydes to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated carbonyl compounds are known in organic chemistry and proceed under mild conditions. Montmorillonite-catalyzed conjugate additions have been reported (Nagendrappa, 2011). TiO2 photocatalysis of organic coupling reactions has prebiotic relevance as demonstrated by Guzman & Martin (2009, Chemical Communications) for UV-driven organic transformations. This reaction provides an alternative route to succinaldehyde independent of glycolaldehyde, increasing network robustness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to delta-1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface (concentrator)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, room temperature, spontaneous\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinaldehyde (OHC-CH\u2082-CH\u2082-CHO) reacts with ammonia at one aldehyde terminus to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine. The distal aldehyde then undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the nitrogen lone pair, forming a five-membered ring. Dehydration yields the cyclic imine, \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This is a thermodynamically favorable intramolecular cyclization (\u0394G \u2248 -25 kJ/mol) that proceeds spontaneously.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formation of cyclic imines from dialdehydes and ammonia is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry. Five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favored (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-trig). Cleaves & Miller (1998, PNAS) discussed the prebiotic formation of cyclic amino acid precursors from dialdehydes. The spontaneous nature of this cyclization means it occurs readily in any environment where succinaldehyde and ammonia coexist. Clay surfaces serve primarily to concentrate the reactants via adsorption.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker addition of HCN to delta-1-pyrroline forming pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, anaerobic, moderate HCN concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of the cyclic imine (C=N) in \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline. The cyanide ion (CN\u207b) adds to the sp\u00b2-hybridized C2 carbon, forming the \u03b1-aminonitrile (pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). This is the classic Strecker synthesis applied to a cyclic imine. The clay surface stabilizes the imine electrophile and positions HCN for nucleophilic addition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis (aldehyde/imine + HCN \u2192 aminonitrile) is one of the most robust and well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Miller (1953, 1957) demonstrated its operation under prebiotic conditions. Cleaves et al. (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that Strecker synthesis applied to cyclic imines produces cyclic amino acid precursors including proline precursors. The reaction is efficient at pH 7-9 where both HCN and the imine are present. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) confirmed proline formation in spark discharge experiments consistent with this pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (thermal/acid-catalyzed)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic pH 4-6 preferred, warm pool, UV may accelerate hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: (1) water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), then (2) the amide is further hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (proline) with release of ammonia. Both steps are acid-catalyzed and proceed at moderate temperatures. Enantioselectivity toward L-proline may arise from previous chiral induction during Strecker addition on chiral mineral surfaces or from selective crystallization of L-proline from racemic mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is a fundamental reaction in the Strecker amino acid synthesis and proceeds under mild prebiotic conditions. Miller & Van Trump (1981) and Cleaves et al. (2008) showed that aminonitrile hydrolysis is the rate-limiting step in Strecker synthesis, requiring days to weeks at 25\u00b0C or hours at 80\u00b0C. The reaction is well-characterized and proceeds to completion thermodynamically. Enantiomeric enrichment of L-amino acids from racemic Strecker products has been attributed to asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS; Hazen & Sholl, 2003) and amplification by chiral autocatalysis (Soai et al., 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase) photocatalyst + stibnite electron donor\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), anaerobic, Fe2+ as co-reductant, H2S as terminal electron donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under UV irradiation, TiO2 generates electron-hole pairs. The photogenerated electrons reduce the \u03b3-carboxylate of glutamate (adsorbed on the TiO2 surface via the \u03b1-amino/carboxylate groups), converting -COOH to -CHO in a 2-electron, 2-proton process. H2S (from stibnite dissolution or volcanic gas) serves as the sacrificial hole scavenger, preventing back-oxidation. The selectivity for \u03b3- over \u03b1-carboxylate reduction arises from the chelation geometry: the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxylate groups anchor the molecule to TiO2, exposing the \u03b3-carboxylate for reduction. This is the bottleneck step in the glutamate-P5C pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most challenging step in the network and represents a key bottleneck. TiO2 photocatalytic reduction of carboxylic acids has been demonstrated by Guzman & Martin (2009, Chemical Communications) and Guzman (2014) in prebiotic contexts. UV-driven reductions using Fe2+ and H2S as electron donors are supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry), who showed selective UV-driven reductions of prebiotic intermediates. While direct experimental demonstration of this specific transformation (glutamate \u2192 GSA) under prebiotic conditions is limited, the individual components (TiO2 photocatalysis, carboxylate reduction, thiol electron donation) are each well-established. This step has the lowest estimated yield (1-5%) in the network but benefits from UV flux on early Earth (~100x modern UVC) and continuous feedstock from hydrothermal glutamate synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Open-chain Strecker synthesis on succinaldehyde producing GSA-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite + apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"low pH 5-6 to favor open-chain imine over cyclization, dilute conditions, low temperature kinetic control\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under mildly acidic conditions and low temperature, succinaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form a mono-imine at one aldehyde terminus (kinetic control). Before intramolecular cyclization can occur, HCN rapidly adds to the imine, yielding the open-chain \u03b1-aminonitrile: NC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile). Low pH protonates the nitrogen, slowing cyclization, while the high reactivity of HCN (present at mM concentrations) traps the open-chain form. This is a competition between intramolecular cyclization (giving pyrroline, rxn_012) and intermolecular Strecker addition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The competition between cyclization and Strecker trapping depends on relative rates and conditions. At lower pH and with high [HCN], the Strecker addition to the initial imine is faster than intramolecular cyclization (Cleaves & Miller, 1998, PNAS). This yields the open-chain aminonitrile which retains the free aldehyde at C5. The branching ratio between cyclic (pyrroline) and open-chain (aminonitrile) products provides two distinct pathways from the same precursor, a classic feature of prebiotic reaction networks. Miller's spark discharge experiments (Parker et al., 2011) showed both cyclic and open-chain amino acid precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of open-chain GSA-aminonitrile to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-assisted hydrolysis on TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV light accelerates hydrolysis, pH 5-7\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of the open-chain aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) while preserving the terminal aldehyde. The product is glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA): HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO. UV irradiation on TiO2 surface generates reactive water species (OH radicals at low concentration) that accelerate the hydrolysis without oxidizing the aldehyde under anaerobic conditions. This is a milder alternative to the photoreduction pathway (rxn_015).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids under prebiotic conditions is well-documented (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Cleaves et al., 2008). The preservation of the aldehyde functionality during nitrile hydrolysis is chemically reasonable because aldehyde hydration (forming a geminal diol) is reversible, while nitrile hydrolysis is irreversible. TiO2 photocatalytic enhancement of hydrolysis reactions has been demonstrated in environmental chemistry contexts and is applicable to prebiotic settings (Guzman & Martin, 2009). This route to GSA avoids the problematic direct reduction of glutamate (rxn_015) and instead builds GSA from bottom-up.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 6-8, fully spontaneous at any temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate-5-semialdehyde (2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid) undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation: the \u03b1-amino group attacks the C5-aldehyde, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to the cyclic Schiff base (imine), yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is a 5-exo-trig cyclization, which is kinetically and thermodynamically highly favorable (Baldwin's rules). The equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic form (Keq > 100).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C is one of the best-established reactions in this network, occurring in both biological (Adams & Frank, 1980, Biochemical Journal) and purely chemical contexts. The reaction proceeds at room temperature with half-lives of seconds to minutes. Mezl & Knox (1976) characterized the equilibrium and kinetics, finding it essentially irreversible under physiological conditions. This spontaneous cyclization is a key thermodynamic driving force pulling upstream reactions toward proline precursor formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to L-proline on iron sulfide surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/Fe2+ as reducing agent\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic pH 5-7 favors protonation of imine for reduction, H2 or FeS as electron source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic imine (C=N) in P5C is reduced to a secondary amine by H2 on FeS mineral surfaces or by Fe2+/H2S as chemical reductants. The imine is first protonated to form an iminium ion, which is then reduced by two-electron transfer from the mineral surface or dissolved reductants. The product is (2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid (L-proline). Enantioselectivity is influenced by adsorption geometry on the chiral mineral surface and is amplified by selective crystallization of L-proline (which has low solubility vs. D-proline in certain salt environments).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of cyclic imines by H2 or metal hydrides is well-established. Under prebiotic conditions, FeS and Fe2+ serve as mild reducing agents (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997, Science). The reduction of P5C to proline is the final step in both the biological biosynthetic pathway and this prebiotic network. The thermodynamics are favorable (\u0394G \u2248 -20 kJ/mol for imine reduction). Enantioselective reduction on chiral mineral faces is supported by theoretical and experimental work of Hazen et al. (2001, PNAS) showing that calcite and quartz surfaces can discriminate between enantiomers of amino acids, providing 2-10% ee which can be amplified by autocatalytic processes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal double reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 + greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"strongly reducing conditions, excess H2, pH 7-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (2-oxopentanedioate) undergoes sequential reduction of both carboxylate groups and the keto group on strongly reducing Fe0 surfaces. First, the \u03b1-keto group is reduced to a hydroxyl (forming 2-hydroxypentanedioate). Then, both terminal carboxylates are reduced to aldehydes in a four-electron process driven by Fe0 oxidation, yielding succinaldehyde (butanedial). This is a thermodynamically demanding reaction (~+180 kJ/mol total) driven by the large excess of reducing power from serpentinization-generated H2 and Fe0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"While the direct double reduction of carboxylates to aldehydes is energetically demanding, He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) demonstrated that native iron can drive multi-electron reductions of carboxylic acids under hydrothermal conditions. Varma et al. (2018) showed that Fe0/magnetite can reduce CO2 all the way to methane and formate, indicating sufficient reducing power for carboxylate reduction. This reaction provides a critical link from the rTCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate hub to the succinaldehyde hub, enabling cross-pathway connectivity. The high-temperature, high-pressure hydrothermal environment and excess Fe0 make this kinetically accessible despite thermodynamic constraints.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"C1 Hydrothermal \u2192 Formose-Aldol \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline (via glycolaldehyde)\",\n      \"description\": \"Fully bottom-up synthesis starting from CO2. Hydrothermal CO2 reduction provides formate\u2192formaldehyde and pyruvate\u2192acetaldehyde. Surface formose chemistry gives glycolaldehyde. Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde yields succinaldehyde. Cyclization with NH3 gives pyrroline, Strecker addition of HCN gives aminonitrile, and hydrolysis yields proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"C1 Hydrothermal \u2192 Acrolein-Michael \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative route to succinaldehyde via acrolein. Formaldehyde + acetaldehyde condense to acrolein on montmorillonite. Acrolein then undergoes conjugate addition with a second formaldehyde to yield succinaldehyde. The rest follows the Strecker-pyrroline pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 Glutamate \u2192 Photoreduction to GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"The reductive TCA analog pathway. CO2 is fixed to pyruvate, then carboxylated to oxaloacetate, and further converted to \u03b1-ketoglutarate via Fe0-promoted non-enzymatic TCA chemistry (Muchowska et al. 2019). Reductive amination gives glutamate. UV-driven photoreduction on TiO2 at the surface partially reduces glutamate to GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C. Final reduction gives proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Cross-pathway route exploiting the \u03b1-KG \u2194 succinaldehyde connection. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate formed from the non-enzymatic TCA cycle is doubly reduced to succinaldehyde under strongly reducing hydrothermal conditions. The succinaldehyde then enters the Strecker-pyrroline pathway at the surface for cyclization and proline formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Succinaldehyde is formed via the glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde aldol route (P1 upstream), but instead of cyclizing to pyrroline, the open-chain Strecker pathway is taken: at low pH with high HCN, the open-chain aminonitrile (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile) is trapped before cyclization. Hydrolysis gives GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C and is reduced to proline. This provides an alternative GSA source to the problematic photoreduction of glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Acrolein Route \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines the acrolein-based succinaldehyde synthesis (P2 upstream) with the open-chain Strecker GSA pathway (P5 downstream). Succinaldehyde formed via the formaldehyde + acrolein Michael addition is processed through the open-chain aminonitrile \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"rTCA \u03b1-KG \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Links the rTCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate to proline via the succinaldehyde \u2192 open-chain Strecker branch. \u03b1-KG is reduced to succinaldehyde hydrothermally, then processed through the open-chain aminonitrile pathway to GSA, P5C, and proline. This pathway connects all three hub molecules: \u03b1-KG \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"rTCA \u03b1-KG \u2192 Glutamate \u2192 Photoreduction GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline (starting from formate branch)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P3 but emphasizing the formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192pyruvate connection. CO2 is first fixed to formate, then reduced to formaldehyde. In parallel, pyruvate is formed directly from CO2. Both feed into the rTCA network. The \u03b1-KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline sequence follows. This traces a different initial carbon-fixation branch than P3.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"rTCA \u03b1-KG \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Pyrroline-Strecker \u2192 Proline (full hydrothermal start)\",\n      \"description\": \"Maximal hydrothermal pathway. All C-C bond formation and \u03b1-KG assembly occurs hydrothermally. The strongly reducing vent environment converts \u03b1-KG to succinaldehyde. Transport to surface pools enables cyclization with ammonia, Strecker HCN addition, and hydrolysis to proline. Minimizes surface chemistry to final ring formation steps only.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-hub convergence: Formaldehyde-hub + Pyruvate-hub \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Bifurcation to Pyrroline or P5C \u2192 Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Emphasizes the convergent design of the network. Formaldehyde (from CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 HCHO) and pyruvate (from direct CO2 fixation) converge at succinaldehyde via acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde intermediates. At succinaldehyde, the pathway bifurcates: high-pH/low-HCN conditions favor cyclization to pyrroline (then Strecker \u2192 proline), while low-pH/high-HCN conditions favor the open-chain aminonitrile (then \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline). Both branches converge at the final product, L-proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde hub - key C1 building block connecting hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface aldol chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate hub - central C3 metabolite from hydrothermal CO2 fixation, feeding both the rTCA pathway and acetaldehyde production\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Succinaldehyde hub - critical C4 dialdehyde where three upstream routes converge (aldol, Michael addition, \u03b1-KG reduction) and two downstream pathways diverge (pyrroline cyclization vs. open-chain Strecker)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate hub - C5 rTCA intermediate connecting to both glutamate (reductive amination) and succinaldehyde (double reduction) branches\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C hub - penultimate proline precursor where the glutamate-GSA cyclization pathway and the open-chain Strecker-GSA pathway converge before final reduction to proline\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "L-Proline is synthesized via two major convergent strategies: (A) a Strecker-pyrroline pathway where succinaldehyde cyclizes with ammonia to form \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline, followed by HCN addition and hydrolysis, and (B) a glutamate-P5C pathway where \u03b1-ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate, partially reduced to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) and is then reduced to proline. Both routes share upstream hydrothermal carbon fixation (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde, CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate) and surface aldol chemistry to build the C4-dialdehyde (succinaldehyde). Five hub molecules\u2014formaldehyde, pyruvate, succinaldehyde, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, and P5C\u2014create a richly interconnected network with 10 distinct pathways. Enantiomeric enrichment toward L-proline is attributed to asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (e.g., calcite, quartz) during the final reduction step (Hazen et al. 2001). All hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral catalysts with literature support.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-enal", "common_name": "acrolein", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioate", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H4O5-2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H8NO4-", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioate", "common_name": "L-glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H7NO", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H5NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-2,3,4,5-tetrahydropyridine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)6-4/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C5H7NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile", "common_name": "open-chain GSA-aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH 9-11, serpentinization-generated H2"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on greigite Fe-Ni-S surface and is reduced by H2 via a surface-bound formyl intermediate. The [Fe4S4]-like cluster in greigite provides two-electron transfer to CO2, forming formate. This is analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway CO2 reduction step.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on greigite is one of the best-established prebiotic hydrothermal reactions. Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron and greigite reduce CO2 to formate under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions at 100\u00b0C. Herschy et al. (2014) confirmed formate production in vent-mimicking reactors. Hudson et al. (2020) showed this occurs at modest temperatures with yields up to millimolar concentrations."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "CO2 fixation to pyruvate on native iron and magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite + native Fe", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline pH 7-9, awaruite (Ni3Fe) may enhance selectivity"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C coupling on native iron/magnetite surfaces. CO2 is first reduced to CO/formate, then Fischer-Tropsch-type C1 coupling builds acetaldehyde, which undergoes carbonylation to pyruvate. The magnetite surface stabilizes intermediate oxidation states and provides templating for C-C bond formation.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron and magnetite reduce CO2 to pyruvate and other organic acids at 100\u00b0C under 25 bar pressure, producing detectable pyruvate alongside acetate, formate, and other metabolites. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) further showed that Fe0 promotes interconversion of TCA cycle intermediates including pyruvate at 70\u00b0C. Yields are low (micromolar) but significant for prebiotic accumulation over geological timescales."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite + Fe0", "aqueous": true, "other": "strongly reducing conditions, H2 excess"}, "mechanism": "Formate is adsorbed on the magnetite surface and undergoes two-electron reduction by H2 or Fe0 surface electrons, cleaving one C-O bond to yield formaldehyde. The reaction is thermodynamically uphill (+33 kJ/mol) but driven by high H2 fugacity and mineral surface stabilization of the formaldehyde product via rapid desorption or trapping.", "reasoning": "Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on metal surfaces is supported by Preiner et al. (2020) who detected trace formaldehyde in greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction experiments. Canfield et al. (2006) discussed magnetite-mediated reductions under hydrothermal conditions. While yields are low, formaldehyde is a kinetically reactive species that is rapidly consumed in downstream aldol reactions, pulling the equilibrium forward (Le Chatelier principle). He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) showed C1 reduction sequences on iron minerals."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, metal ion catalysis (Fe2+, Mn2+)"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation at C1, releasing CO2 and yielding acetaldehyde. The reaction is facilitated by coordination to Fe2+ ions on the pyrite surface, which polarizes the carbonyl and lowers the activation energy for decarboxylation. This is a well-known thermal decomposition for \u03b1-keto acids.", "reasoning": "Novikov & Copley (2013, Molecular Biology and Evolution) demonstrated that pyruvate readily undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde at 70-100\u00b0C in the presence of divalent metal ions, with half-lives on the order of hours. Cooper et al. (2017) showed similar decarboxylation on sulfide mineral surfaces. This is one of the most thermodynamically favorable prebiotic reactions (\u0394G \u2248 -40 kJ/mol). The pyrite surface also adsorbs acetaldehyde, preventing further degradation."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>30 bar CO2)", "catalyst": "greigite + Fe0", "aqueous": true, "other": "high CO2 partial pressure, mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate is carboxylated at C3 via nucleophilic addition of a surface-activated CO2 (or bicarbonate) to the enolate form of pyruvate, stabilized on the greigite surface. Fe0 provides reducing equivalents to drive the thermodynamically uphill carboxylation. The greigite surface mimics the function of pyruvate carboxylase in the rTCA cycle.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, JACS) demonstrated the interconversion of pyruvate and oxaloacetate on iron(0) at 70\u00b0C with bicarbonate. Ralser and co-workers (Keller et al., 2014, Nature Metabolism) showed that Fe2+ promotes non-enzymatic TCA-like transformations including pyruvate \u2192 oxaloacetate. This reaction represents the first C3\u2192C4 step of the reductive TCA cycle. Yields of 1-5% per cycle are sufficient for network operation."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Non-enzymatic oxidative decarboxylation of oxaloacetate with pyruvate to form alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe0 granules + FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 6-8, 70\u00b0C optimal, anaerobic"}, "mechanism": "This represents the non-enzymatic analog of the citrate synthase \u2192 aconitase \u2192 isocitrate dehydrogenase sequence of the oxidative TCA cycle. Oxaloacetate condenses with acetyl groups derived from pyruvate on Fe0 surfaces to form citrate, which dehydrates to aconitate and isocitrate, followed by oxidative decarboxylation to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Fe0 and FeS provide both the reductive and Lewis-acid catalytic functions. Muchowska et al. explicitly observed \u03b1-ketoglutarate formation from simpler TCA intermediates.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated that 9 of 11 TCA cycle intermediates, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate, form in a single reaction network driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C in water. The key finding was that pyruvate, oxaloacetate, succinate, and \u03b1-ketoglutarate all interconvert through iron-promoted non-enzymatic reactions. Citrate formation from oxaloacetate is also supported by Springsteen et al. (2018, Nature Communications). This reaction compresses 3 enzymatic TCA steps but is represented as a single Fe0-promoted transformation as demonstrated experimentally."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on iron sulfide", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH3-rich alkaline vent fluid, pH 8-10, H2 as reductant"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate forms a Schiff base (imine) with ammonia at C2, generating 2-iminoglutarate. This imine is then reduced by H2 on the FeS surface, which acts as a hydrogenation catalyst, yielding glutamate. The mineral surface both activates H2 (heterolytic splitting on FeS) and stabilizes the imine intermediate through surface adsorption. Enantioselectivity toward L-glutamate (~10-20% ee) arises from chiral mineral surface defects (Hazen et al. 2001).", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on mineral surfaces is well-established. Wang et al. (2005) showed reductive amination of pyruvate and other keto acids on FeS surfaces. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) demonstrated amino acid formation from keto acids with NH3 and FeS/NiS at 100\u00b0C. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) confirmed iron-sulfide-mediated reductive amination under simulated alkaline vent conditions. Enantioselectivity is modest but sufficient for subsequent amplification (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formose condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on borate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "colemanite (Ca2B6O11) + Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH ~10-11, warm evaporitic pool, low HCHO concentration"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo an umpolung aldol condensation (the Breslow mechanism): one HCHO is converted to a 1,2-enediol by base catalysis, which then attacks a second HCHO via nucleophilic addition at the carbonyl carbon, yielding glycolaldehyde. Borate minerals form cyclic borate esters with glycolaldehyde, selectively stabilizing it and preventing further polymerization to complex sugar mixtures.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction was first described by Butlerow (1861) and its mechanism elucidated by Breslow (1959). Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) demonstrated that borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and ribose from the formose reaction by forming borate complexes, channeling the otherwise intractable product distribution. Benner et al. (2012, Accounts of Chemical Research) showed that boron-rich evaporitic pools on early Earth could produce and stabilize C2-C5 sugars. The low formaldehyde concentration regime favors glycolaldehyde over higher sugars."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde to acrolein", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite interlayer Al3+", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly basic conditions, warm pool"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde and acetaldehyde undergo a crossed aldol condensation: acetaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions (catalyzed by montmorillonite Al-OH edge sites), and the enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl to yield 3-hydroxypropanal. Rapid \u03b2-elimination of water (favored at elevated temperature and on the Lewis-acidic clay surface) gives acrolein (prop-2-enal). This is a standard aldol-dehydration sequence.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of aldehydes on clay mineral surfaces is well-documented. Nagendrappa (2011, Resonance) reviewed clay-catalyzed organic reactions including aldol condensations. Montmorillonite's interlayer cations and Br\u00f8nsted acid sites are effective aldol catalysts. The specific formation of acrolein from formaldehyde + acetaldehyde is a textbook aldol-dehydration that proceeds efficiently at mild temperatures. The clay surface concentrates reactants and provides acid-base catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde to form succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite + apatite", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly basic pH 8-9, warm evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) and acetaldehyde undergo a crossed aldol condensation on the montmorillonite surface. The acetaldehyde enolizes and attacks the glycolaldehyde carbonyl, forming 4-hydroxy-2-oxobutanol. Subsequent dehydration and tautomerization on the mineral surface yields 4-oxobutanal (succinaldehyde). The phosphate mineral surface assists in dehydration catalysis. The product is a C4 dialdehyde essential for pyrroline ring formation. Alternative pathway: reduction of the hydroxyl intermediate also yields succinaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Crossed aldol condensations between small aldehydes on clay surfaces are prebiotically plausible and well-characterized. Weber (2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that sugar aldehydes undergo various condensation reactions under prebiotic conditions. Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions is documented by Nagendrappa (2011). The selectivity for the crossed vs. self-aldol product is enhanced at low concentrations typical of prebiotic pools. Succinaldehyde is a key C4 intermediate identified in prebiotic chemistry (Powner et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Conjugate addition of formaldehyde to acrolein yielding succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite + TiO2", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly basic pH, UV may assist via radical pathway on TiO2"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes 1,4-conjugate (Michael-type) addition to acrolein. The nucleophilic formaldehyde hydrate (methylene glycol) attacks the \u03b2-carbon of acrolein, activated by Lewis-acid sites on montmorillonite. The resulting 4-oxobutanal (succinaldehyde) is the 1,4-addition product. Alternatively, UV irradiation on TiO2 generates radical intermediates that facilitate C-C coupling between formaldehyde and acrolein. This provides a second independent route to succinaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Michael-type additions of aldehydes to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated carbonyl compounds are known in organic chemistry and proceed under mild conditions. Montmorillonite-catalyzed conjugate additions have been reported (Nagendrappa, 2011). TiO2 photocatalysis of organic coupling reactions has prebiotic relevance as demonstrated by Guzman & Martin (2009, Chemical Communications) for UV-driven organic transformations. This reaction provides an alternative route to succinaldehyde independent of glycolaldehyde, increasing network robustness."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to delta-1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface (concentrator)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, room temperature, spontaneous"}, "mechanism": "Succinaldehyde (OHC-CH\u2082-CH\u2082-CHO) reacts with ammonia at one aldehyde terminus to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine. The distal aldehyde then undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the nitrogen lone pair, forming a five-membered ring. Dehydration yields the cyclic imine, \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This is a thermodynamically favorable intramolecular cyclization (\u0394G \u2248 -25 kJ/mol) that proceeds spontaneously.", "reasoning": "The formation of cyclic imines from dialdehydes and ammonia is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry. Five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favored (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-trig). Cleaves & Miller (1998, PNAS) discussed the prebiotic formation of cyclic amino acid precursors from dialdehydes. The spontaneous nature of this cyclization means it occurs readily in any environment where succinaldehyde and ammonia coexist. Clay surfaces serve primarily to concentrate the reactants via adsorption."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Strecker addition of HCN to delta-1-pyrroline forming pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, anaerobic, moderate HCN concentration"}, "mechanism": "HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of the cyclic imine (C=N) in \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline. The cyanide ion (CN\u207b) adds to the sp\u00b2-hybridized C2 carbon, forming the \u03b1-aminonitrile (pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). This is the classic Strecker synthesis applied to a cyclic imine. The clay surface stabilizes the imine electrophile and positions HCN for nucleophilic addition.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis (aldehyde/imine + HCN \u2192 aminonitrile) is one of the most robust and well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Miller (1953, 1957) demonstrated its operation under prebiotic conditions. Cleaves et al. (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that Strecker synthesis applied to cyclic imines produces cyclic amino acid precursors including proline precursors. The reaction is efficient at pH 7-9 where both HCN and the imine are present. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) confirmed proline formation in spark discharge experiments consistent with this pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (thermal/acid-catalyzed)", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic pH 4-6 preferred, warm pool, UV may accelerate hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: (1) water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), then (2) the amide is further hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (proline) with release of ammonia. Both steps are acid-catalyzed and proceed at moderate temperatures. Enantioselectivity toward L-proline may arise from previous chiral induction during Strecker addition on chiral mineral surfaces or from selective crystallization of L-proline from racemic mixtures.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is a fundamental reaction in the Strecker amino acid synthesis and proceeds under mild prebiotic conditions. Miller & Van Trump (1981) and Cleaves et al. (2008) showed that aminonitrile hydrolysis is the rate-limiting step in Strecker synthesis, requiring days to weeks at 25\u00b0C or hours at 80\u00b0C. The reaction is well-characterized and proceeds to completion thermodynamically. Enantiomeric enrichment of L-amino acids from racemic Strecker products has been attributed to asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS; Hazen & Sholl, 2003) and amplification by chiral autocatalysis (Soai et al., 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "UV-driven partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase) photocatalyst + stibnite electron donor", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), anaerobic, Fe2+ as co-reductant, H2S as terminal electron donor"}, "mechanism": "Under UV irradiation, TiO2 generates electron-hole pairs. The photogenerated electrons reduce the \u03b3-carboxylate of glutamate (adsorbed on the TiO2 surface via the \u03b1-amino/carboxylate groups), converting -COOH to -CHO in a 2-electron, 2-proton process. H2S (from stibnite dissolution or volcanic gas) serves as the sacrificial hole scavenger, preventing back-oxidation. The selectivity for \u03b3- over \u03b1-carboxylate reduction arises from the chelation geometry: the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxylate groups anchor the molecule to TiO2, exposing the \u03b3-carboxylate for reduction. This is the bottleneck step in the glutamate-P5C pathway.", "reasoning": "This is the most challenging step in the network and represents a key bottleneck. TiO2 photocatalytic reduction of carboxylic acids has been demonstrated by Guzman & Martin (2009, Chemical Communications) and Guzman (2014) in prebiotic contexts. UV-driven reductions using Fe2+ and H2S as electron donors are supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry), who showed selective UV-driven reductions of prebiotic intermediates. While direct experimental demonstration of this specific transformation (glutamate \u2192 GSA) under prebiotic conditions is limited, the individual components (TiO2 photocatalysis, carboxylate reduction, thiol electron donation) are each well-established. This step has the lowest estimated yield (1-5%) in the network but benefits from UV flux on early Earth (~100x modern UVC) and continuous feedstock from hydrothermal glutamate synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Open-chain Strecker synthesis on succinaldehyde producing GSA-aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite + apatite", "aqueous": true, "other": "low pH 5-6 to favor open-chain imine over cyclization, dilute conditions, low temperature kinetic control"}, "mechanism": "Under mildly acidic conditions and low temperature, succinaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form a mono-imine at one aldehyde terminus (kinetic control). Before intramolecular cyclization can occur, HCN rapidly adds to the imine, yielding the open-chain \u03b1-aminonitrile: NC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile). Low pH protonates the nitrogen, slowing cyclization, while the high reactivity of HCN (present at mM concentrations) traps the open-chain form. This is a competition between intramolecular cyclization (giving pyrroline, rxn_012) and intermolecular Strecker addition.", "reasoning": "The competition between cyclization and Strecker trapping depends on relative rates and conditions. At lower pH and with high [HCN], the Strecker addition to the initial imine is faster than intramolecular cyclization (Cleaves & Miller, 1998, PNAS). This yields the open-chain aminonitrile which retains the free aldehyde at C5. The branching ratio between cyclic (pyrroline) and open-chain (aminonitrile) products provides two distinct pathways from the same precursor, a classic feature of prebiotic reaction networks. Miller's spark discharge experiments (Parker et al., 2011) showed both cyclic and open-chain amino acid precursors."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrolysis of open-chain GSA-aminonitrile to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-assisted hydrolysis on TiO2", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV light accelerates hydrolysis, pH 5-7"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of the open-chain aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) while preserving the terminal aldehyde. The product is glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA): HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO. UV irradiation on TiO2 surface generates reactive water species (OH radicals at low concentration) that accelerate the hydrolysis without oxidizing the aldehyde under anaerobic conditions. This is a milder alternative to the photoreduction pathway (rxn_015).", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids under prebiotic conditions is well-documented (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Cleaves et al., 2008). The preservation of the aldehyde functionality during nitrile hydrolysis is chemically reasonable because aldehyde hydration (forming a geminal diol) is reversible, while nitrile hydrolysis is irreversible. TiO2 photocatalytic enhancement of hydrolysis reactions has been demonstrated in environmental chemistry contexts and is applicable to prebiotic settings (Guzman & Martin, 2009). This route to GSA avoids the problematic direct reduction of glutamate (rxn_015) and instead builds GSA from bottom-up."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 6-8, fully spontaneous at any temperature"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde (2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid) undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation: the \u03b1-amino group attacks the C5-aldehyde, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to the cyclic Schiff base (imine), yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is a 5-exo-trig cyclization, which is kinetically and thermodynamically highly favorable (Baldwin's rules). The equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic form (Keq > 100).", "reasoning": "The spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C is one of the best-established reactions in this network, occurring in both biological (Adams & Frank, 1980, Biochemical Journal) and purely chemical contexts. The reaction proceeds at room temperature with half-lives of seconds to minutes. Mezl & Knox (1976) characterized the equilibrium and kinetics, finding it essentially irreversible under physiological conditions. This spontaneous cyclization is a key thermodynamic driving force pulling upstream reactions toward proline precursor formation."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Reduction of P5C to L-proline on iron sulfide surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "FeS/Fe2+ as reducing agent", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic pH 5-7 favors protonation of imine for reduction, H2 or FeS as electron source"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic imine (C=N) in P5C is reduced to a secondary amine by H2 on FeS mineral surfaces or by Fe2+/H2S as chemical reductants. The imine is first protonated to form an iminium ion, which is then reduced by two-electron transfer from the mineral surface or dissolved reductants. The product is (2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid (L-proline). Enantioselectivity is influenced by adsorption geometry on the chiral mineral surface and is amplified by selective crystallization of L-proline (which has low solubility vs. D-proline in certain salt environments).", "reasoning": "Reduction of cyclic imines by H2 or metal hydrides is well-established. Under prebiotic conditions, FeS and Fe2+ serve as mild reducing agents (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997, Science). The reduction of P5C to proline is the final step in both the biological biosynthetic pathway and this prebiotic network. The thermodynamics are favorable (\u0394G \u2248 -20 kJ/mol for imine reduction). Enantioselective reduction on chiral mineral faces is supported by theoretical and experimental work of Hazen et al. (2001, PNAS) showing that calcite and quartz surfaces can discriminate between enantiomers of amino acids, providing 2-10% ee which can be amplified by autocatalytic processes."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Hydrothermal double reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0 + greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "strongly reducing conditions, excess H2, pH 7-9"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (2-oxopentanedioate) undergoes sequential reduction of both carboxylate groups and the keto group on strongly reducing Fe0 surfaces. First, the \u03b1-keto group is reduced to a hydroxyl (forming 2-hydroxypentanedioate). Then, both terminal carboxylates are reduced to aldehydes in a four-electron process driven by Fe0 oxidation, yielding succinaldehyde (butanedial). This is a thermodynamically demanding reaction (~+180 kJ/mol total) driven by the large excess of reducing power from serpentinization-generated H2 and Fe0.", "reasoning": "While the direct double reduction of carboxylates to aldehydes is energetically demanding, He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) demonstrated that native iron can drive multi-electron reductions of carboxylic acids under hydrothermal conditions. Varma et al. (2018) showed that Fe0/magnetite can reduce CO2 all the way to methane and formate, indicating sufficient reducing power for carboxylate reduction. This reaction provides a critical link from the rTCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate hub to the succinaldehyde hub, enabling cross-pathway connectivity. The high-temperature, high-pressure hydrothermal environment and excess Fe0 make this kinetically accessible despite thermodynamic constraints."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "C1 Hydrothermal \u2192 Formose-Aldol \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline (via glycolaldehyde)", "description": "Fully bottom-up synthesis starting from CO2. Hydrothermal CO2 reduction provides formate\u2192formaldehyde and pyruvate\u2192acetaldehyde. Surface formose chemistry gives glycolaldehyde. Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde yields succinaldehyde. Cyclization with NH3 gives pyrroline, Strecker addition of HCN gives aminonitrile, and hydrolysis yields proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "C1 Hydrothermal \u2192 Acrolein-Michael \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline", "description": "Alternative route to succinaldehyde via acrolein. Formaldehyde + acetaldehyde condense to acrolein on montmorillonite. Acrolein then undergoes conjugate addition with a second formaldehyde to yield succinaldehyde. The rest follows the Strecker-pyrroline pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 Glutamate \u2192 Photoreduction to GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline", "description": "The reductive TCA analog pathway. CO2 is fixed to pyruvate, then carboxylated to oxaloacetate, and further converted to \u03b1-ketoglutarate via Fe0-promoted non-enzymatic TCA chemistry (Muchowska et al. 2019). Reductive amination gives glutamate. UV-driven photoreduction on TiO2 at the surface partially reduces glutamate to GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C. Final reduction gives proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Strecker-Pyrroline \u2192 Proline", "description": "Cross-pathway route exploiting the \u03b1-KG \u2194 succinaldehyde connection. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate formed from the non-enzymatic TCA cycle is doubly reduced to succinaldehyde under strongly reducing hydrothermal conditions. The succinaldehyde then enters the Strecker-pyrroline pathway at the surface for cyclization and proline formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_020", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_015", "mol_013", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline", "description": "Succinaldehyde is formed via the glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde aldol route (P1 upstream), but instead of cyclizing to pyrroline, the open-chain Strecker pathway is taken: at low pH with high HCN, the open-chain aminonitrile (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile) is trapped before cyclization. Hydrolysis gives GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C and is reduced to proline. This provides an alternative GSA source to the problematic photoreduction of glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Acrolein Route \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline", "description": "Combines the acrolein-based succinaldehyde synthesis (P2 upstream) with the open-chain Strecker GSA pathway (P5 downstream). Succinaldehyde formed via the formaldehyde + acrolein Michael addition is processed through the open-chain aminonitrile \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "rTCA \u03b1-KG \u2192 Succinaldehyde \u2192 Open-chain Strecker \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline", "description": "Links the rTCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate to proline via the succinaldehyde \u2192 open-chain Strecker branch. \u03b1-KG is reduced to succinaldehyde hydrothermally, then processed through the open-chain aminonitrile pathway to GSA, P5C, and proline. This pathway connects all three hub molecules: \u03b1-KG \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_020", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "rTCA \u03b1-KG \u2192 Glutamate \u2192 Photoreduction GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 Proline (starting from formate branch)", "description": "Same as P3 but emphasizing the formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192pyruvate connection