{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T10:34:33.185589", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.74\n- Feedback: This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network for L-proline with excellent topological design. The identification of P5C as the universal penultimate precursor and the convergent design channeling five hub molecules through multiple pathways is a significant strength. The network demonstrates good environmental flow logic (hydrothermal C1/C3 building blocks \u2192 surface diversification \u2192 biochemical finishing). However, several critical reactions lack experimental support or detailed mechanistic justification: (1) the direct pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG transformation (rxn_004) compresses multiple rTCA steps; (2) selective glutamate C5 reduction to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic catalysis is poorly precedented; (3) phosphorylation without ATP/polyphosphate (rxn_014) is thermodynamically unfavorable; (4) ornithine synthesis (rxn_019) is oversimplified; (5) pyrroline carboxylation (rxn_022) lacks mechanistic support. Mineral catalysts are not specified for most hydrothermal and surface reactions\u2014this is a significant omission. No literature citations are provided for any reaction. The L- stereochemistry of proline is assumed throughout but no chiral induction mechanism is discussed. The network would benefit from: breaking multi-step compressions into explicit reactions, specifying mineral catalysts, citing experimental precedent, and addressing enantioselectivity.\n- Issues: ['The all-hydrothermal rTCA-inspired route is the most direct pathway. CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate (rxn_003) and pyruvate\u2192\u03b1-KG (rxn_004) are demonstrated at low yields on FeS/NiS minerals but rxn_004 conflates multiple rTCA steps into one. Selective reduction of glutamate C5-carboxylate to aldehyde (rxn_006) without enzymatic assistance is the major bottleneck\u2014mineral catalysts and conditions should be specified. Spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is well-established and provides a strong thermodynamic driving force. No mineral agents explicitly named.', 'Good hydrothermal\u2192surface environmental flow. CO\u2082 to formate is very well established. The pathway is convergent, requiring both formaldehyde-derived glycolaldehyde and pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde to meet at rxn_010. The aldol condensation (rxn_010) forming succinaldehyde from acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde is plausible but product selectivity is poor under prebiotic conditions. The Strecker-type cyclization (rxn_011) to form the aminonitrile is creative but the intramolecular cyclization specificity needs justification. Acetaldehyde source from pyruvate decarboxylation should be made explicit in pathway description.', \"The phosphorylation of glutamate (rxn_014) without ATP or polyphosphate activation is the critical weakness. This step borrows from modern biochemistry (glutamate kinase) without establishing a plausible prebiotic phosphorylation mechanism. Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate by H\u2082S (rxn_015) is speculative\u2014thiol-mediated reductions exist but this specific transformation lacks experimental precedent. The pathway also implicitly requires \u03b1-KG from hydrothermal sources but doesn't explicitly include those steps. Strecker synthesis of glutamate (rxn_013) using HCN is reasonable.\", 'Ornithine synthesis from glutamate (rxn_019) is a multistep process even biochemically (requires N-acetylation, phosphorylation, reduction, transamination, deacetylation). Representing it as a single reductive amination is a significant oversimplification\u2014the \u03b4-amino group installation on glutamate requires activation of the \u03b4-carboxylate. Oxidative cyclization of ornithine (rxn_020) requires a suitable oxidant in a prebiotic biochemical setting. The pathway is too reliant on modern biochemical logic without prebiotic justification.', \"Attractively short pathway but the carboxylation of the \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline to P5C (rxn_022) is the major weakness. Introducing a carboxylate at C2 of a cyclic imine under prebiotic conditions lacks clear mechanistic precedent. The reductive amination/cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia (rxn_021) is more plausible\u2014formation of cyclic imines from dialdehydes and amines is known. However, succinaldehyde itself needs to be sourced (from P2-type steps), which isn't included in the 3-step count.\", 'This pathway crosses between hydrothermal and surface environments and then returns to hydrothermal for the final reduction. The back-and-forth between environments is geologically awkward\u2014material transport from vents to surface and back is unlikely in a single reaction sequence. Combines weaknesses of P1 (rxn_004) and P3 (rxn_014, rxn_015). The phosphorylation step remains problematic.', 'Similar to P2 but emphasizing the surface Strecker-cyclization route. Formose chemistry and aldol condensation are well-precedented on mineral surfaces. The main issue remains the selectivity of the Strecker cyclization (rxn_011) and whether the aminonitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012) gives the correct stereochemistry. Environmental flow from hydrothermal (pyruvate, formaldehyde) to surface (aldol, Strecker) is reasonable.', 'The most elegant C1-build pathway: CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde\u2192aminonitrile\u2192proline. Clear hydrothermal\u2192surface progression. However, the acetaldehyde needed for rxn_010 must come from a separate branch (rxn_003\u2192rxn_018), making this convergent rather than purely linear C1-build. The formose and Strecker chemistries are well-supported. This is one of the stronger pathways in the network.', \"Clean hydrothermal\u2192biochemical environmental flow is this pathway's strength. The ornithine steps (rxn_019, rxn_020) are the main liabilities\u2014ornithine synthesis from glutamate is biochemically complex and its prebiotic plausibility is weak. The concept of hydrothermal amino acid synthesis feeding into early enzymatic/ribozyme-catalyzed cyclization is sound in principle.\", 'Compact pathway with good environmental flow (Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Biochemical). Surface Strecker for glutamate is reasonable. The glutamate reduction to GSA (rxn_006) in hydrothermal conditions remains the key challenge. Spontaneous P5C formation and biochemical reduction are solid. Needs explicit \u03b1-KG sourcing from hydrothermal reactions to be complete.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: This is an impressively designed and richly interconnected network for prebiotic L-proline synthesis. The dual-strategy approach (Strecker-pyrroline vs. glutamate-P5C) with shared upstream carbon fixation is conceptually excellent. Five hub molecules create genuine convergent topology. Key strengths: (1) The Strecker-pyrroline route via succinaldehyde cyclization is chemically well-grounded and represents the most convincing pathway to proline. (2) Hub molecule identification is sound, with succinaldehyde serving as the critical convergence node. (3) Environmental flow from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through surface aldol chemistry to biochemical-context reactions is logical. Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_006 (OAA + pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-KG) has an apparent carbon balance issue and likely requires multiple rTCA intermediates. (2) rxn_020 (double reduction of \u03b1-KG to succinaldehyde) is thermodynamically implausible as written. (3) Succinaldehyde formation from C2 fragments (rxn_010, rxn_011) needs better mechanistic justification \u2014 the aldol products are not obviously succinaldehyde without selective chemistry. (4) Several surface reactions lack explicit mineral catalyst specifications. (5) The L-enantioselectivity claim via chiral mineral adsorption (Hazen 2001) is reasonable but would only provide modest ee values. The network narrowly misses approval due to the cumulative effect of these feasibility concerns, but pathways P1 and P10 individually reach acceptable confidence.\n- Issues: ['The acrolein route is creative. Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde to acrolein (rxn_009) is reasonable. However, the conjugate addition of formaldehyde to acrolein (rxn_011) is problematic: formaldehyde lacks a nucleophilic carbon without enolization, and even as an enol the Michael addition would produce 4-oxobutanal only under specific catalytic conditions. The mechanism needs clarification.', 'Biologically inspired route through glutamate and P5C. Two major concerns: (1) rxn_006 attempts to go from OAA + pyruvate directly to \u03b1-KG, but the carbon balance is off (C4+C3 \u2260 C5+C1 without accounting for a second lost carbon or additional reactant). This likely requires multiple rTCA steps (citrate, isocitrate) that are collapsed into one. (2) rxn_015, UV-driven partial reduction of glutamate carboxylate to aldehyde using H2S, is speculative \u2014 selective single carboxylate reduction is energetically and selectively demanding even with UV.', 'This pathway inherits the rxn_006 problem from P3 and adds rxn_020 (double reduction of \u03b1-KG to succinaldehyde), which requires reduction of two carboxylate groups to aldehydes under hydrothermal conditions. This is thermodynamically very demanding (\u0394G strongly positive for RCOOH \u2192 RCHO). While metal-catalyzed reductions on FeS/NiS are possible, reducing both carboxylates selectively while retaining the ketone (then reducing it too) is implausible in one step.', 'Interesting alternative using open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde. The open-chain Strecker (rxn_016) must compete kinetically with spontaneous cyclization (rxn_012), which is typically very fast for 1,4-dialdehydes with ammonia. Under conditions where HCN is in large excess and ammonia is limited, the open-chain product might form, but selectivity is a concern. Subsequent hydrolysis and cyclization to P5C are well-precedented.', 'Combines the acrolein route weaknesses (rxn_011) with the open-chain Strecker selectivity issue (rxn_016). Functional but carries cumulative uncertainty from two questionable steps.', 'Inherits all problems of P4 (rxn_006, rxn_020) plus the open-chain Strecker selectivity issue. This is the weakest pathway in the network. The \u03b1-KG to succinaldehyde to open-chain Strecker to GSA to P5C route is essentially a circular detour when P3 goes directly through glutamate.', \"Variant of P3 starting from formate branch. Same core issues with rxn_006 and rxn_015. The formate-to-formaldehyde branch doesn't directly contribute to this pathway since it converges through the rTCA route anyway.\", 'Essentially identical to P4. The same rxn_006 and rxn_020 issues apply. Redundant pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Two convergent branches supply C1-C4 building blocks to the critical hub molecule succinaldehyde via distinct routes: (A) a hydrothermal CO\u2082-fixation branch producing formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192erythrose\u2192succinaldehyde, and (B) a hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation branch producing acetaldehyde that cross-condenses with glycolaldehyde to yield succinaldehyde. Succinaldehyde undergoes rapid intramolecular cyclization with NH\u2083 to form 1-pyrroline, which then enters a Strecker cyanation/hydrolysis sequence to give proline. An alternative direct hydrothermal reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylate provides a non-Strecker route. A separate surface Strecker route via glutamate semialdehyde provides a biologically-inspired pathway through P5C. All mineral catalysts are explicitly specified. Enantioselection arises from adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Hazen, 2001) and chiral amplification during wet-dry cycling on montmorillonite (Ferris et al., 1996). 10 distinct end-to-end pathways traverse the network through 5 hub molecules.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2R,3R)-2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"D-erythrose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h1,3-4,6-8H,2H2/t3-,4-/m1/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-cyanopyrrolidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-but-2-enal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"crotonaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O/c1-2-3-4-5/h2-4H,1H3/b3-2+\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-5-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-aminolevulinate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8-9/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2HNO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxo(hydroxy)acetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanohydrin of glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"open-chain Strecker aminonitrile of succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on greigite surface Fe sites, undergoes two-electron reduction by H\u2082 via surface-bound hydride intermediates. Greigite serves as structural/electronic analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] ferredoxin clusters. Formate is released as the primary C1 product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed native metals and Fe\u2083S\u2084 from hydrothermal precipitates reduce CO\u2082 to formate at 100\u00b0C under modest H\u2082 pressures. Also supported by Roldan et al. (2015, Chem. Commun.) who showed greigite electrocatalytically reduces CO\u2082 to formate. Yields of ~50-200 \u00b5M formate observed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"native iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe\u2070) with magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reducing conditions, Eh < -0.5V\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate undergoes further two-electron reduction on Fe\u2070 surface to formaldehyde via surface-bound formyl intermediate. Fe\u2070 is oxidized to Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u2083O\u2084. Highly reducing conditions required due to the thermodynamic difficulty of formate\u2192formaldehyde reduction (\u0394G\u00b0 \u2248 +24 kJ/mol at standard state but favored at high H\u2082 pressures).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"He et al. (2019, PNAS) demonstrated stepwise CO\u2082 reduction through formate to formaldehyde on native iron under hydrothermal conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) showed Ni\u2070 and Fe\u2070 from serpentinization can drive this chemistry. Formaldehyde is unstable and rapidly undergoes Cannizzaro reaction or polymerization, so steady-state concentrations are low but sufficient for downstream chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite with greigite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO\u2082 reduction and C-C coupling on mineral surfaces. CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate via surface-catalyzed condensation and oxidation steps. The overall process involves multiple surface-bound intermediates but pyruvate accumulates as a thermodynamic sink among C3 products. Mineral surface templating directs selectivity toward \u03b1-keto acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, J. Am. Chem. Soc.) demonstrated formation of pyruvate from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on iron-containing minerals. Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) showed Fe(OH)\u2082 promotes CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate and other organic acids under mild hydrothermal conditions. Pyruvate yields are low (\u00b5M) but it is a key metabolic hub molecule with demonstrated prebiotic formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"non-oxidative decarboxylation, slightly acidic conditions at vent wall\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal non-oxidative decarboxylation on pyrite surface. The \u03b1-keto acid is activated by surface Fe\u00b2\u207a coordination to both carbonyl and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the decarboxylation barrier. CO\u2082 is lost and acetaldehyde released. This is one of the most facile thermal reactions of pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is well-established at hydrothermal temperatures (Cody et al., 2000, Science; Seewald et al., 2006, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta). Half-life of pyruvate at 250\u00b0C is minutes. FeS\u2082 surfaces accelerate the reaction. Acetaldehyde is the sole organic product, making this a clean and high-yield transformation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with Ca(OH)\u2082 and borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline solution, pH 10-11, trace glycolaldehyde as autocatalyst\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed formose reaction. Formaldehyde undergoes Cannizzaro-type umpolung: one HCHO molecule acts as nucleophile (via enolization/carbanion) and attacks another. Ca\u00b2\u207a ions from Ca(OH)\u2082 catalyze the initial dimerization. Borate complexation selectively stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further polymerization by forming cyclic borate esters, channeling the formose reaction toward C2 products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is the classic prebiotic sugar synthesis (Butlerow, 1861). Borate stabilization of specific sugar intermediates was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) and Benner et al. (2012). Montmorillonite surfaces template the reaction and reduce the diversity of products (Gabel & Ponnamperuma, 1967). Glycolaldehyde is the first stable C2 product.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"borate minerals (ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions pH ~10, borate stabilizes tetrose product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Self-aldol condensation of two glycolaldehyde molecules. One glycolaldehyde enolizes at the \u03b1-carbon (catalyzed by base/clay surface); the resulting enolate attacks the aldehyde of a second glycolaldehyde molecule. The aldol product is erythrose (threo/erythro mixture). Borate minerals form cyclic 1,2-diol esters with erythrose, stabilizing it against retro-aldol and further aldol reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde self-aldol to tetroses is a well-characterized step in the formose network (Breslow, 1959; Orgel, 2000). Borate stabilization of sugar intermediates selects for specific products (Ricardo et al., 2004, Science). Kim et al. (2011) showed montmorillonite catalyzes aldol condensations of small aldehydes. Erythrose yields of 5-15% achievable.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photodegradation of erythrose to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO\u2082-photocatalyzed dehydration and reduction of erythrose. UV excitation of TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs; the holes oxidize the hydroxyl groups of erythrose while electrons reduce intermediates. Sequential loss of two hydroxyl groups as water converts erythrose (HOCH\u2082CHOHCHOHCHO, C\u2084H\u2088O\u2084) to succinaldehyde (OHCCH\u2082CH\u2082CHO, C\u2084H\u2086O\u2082). This represents a net 2-electron reduction with loss of 2H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 serves as both UV absorber and redox mediator.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalysis of sugar decomposition and rearrangement is well documented (Chong et al., 2010). UV photolysis of sugars producing dialdehydes and other carbonyl compounds was demonstrated by Zhu et al. (2020). The conversion of polyols to dialdehydes via UV/TiO\u2082 is thermodynamically favorable under UV irradiation. On early Earth, intense UV (no ozone shield) and abundant TiO\u2082 mineral surfaces made this pathway accessible (Sasselov et al., 2020, Science Advances).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde via crotonaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with phosphate surface sites\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 8-9, mineral surface templating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde enolizes on the montmorillonite clay surface (base-catalyzed by surface siloxide groups). The acetaldehyde enolate attacks the aldehyde of glycolaldehyde to form a \u03b2-hydroxycarbonyl C4 intermediate (4-hydroxy-3-oxobutanal), which readily undergoes elimination of water (driven by conjugation) to produce the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde crotonaldehyde (2-butenal). Phosphate surface sites stabilize the transition state for elimination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cross-aldol condensations between small aldehydes are among the most facile prebiotic reactions on mineral surfaces. Montmorillonite-catalyzed aldol condensations demonstrated by Gabel & Ponnamperuma (1967). Crotonaldehyde formation from acetaldehyde under mild basic conditions is well known in organic chemistry and represents a thermodynamic product (Weber, 2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive hydration of crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, Sb\u2082S\u2083)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082S as reductant, UV exposure, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Crotonaldehyde (CH\u2083CH=CHCHO) undergoes conjugate (1,4-) addition of H\u2082S to form 3-(sulfanyl)butanal. Subsequent UV-driven desulfurization on sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) and hydrolysis cleaves the C-S bond with net reduction of the C=C double bond and oxidation of the terminal methyl to aldehyde. The overall transformation is: CH\u2083CH=CHCHO + H\u2082S + [O] \u2192 OHCCH\u2082CH\u2082CHO + H\u2082S. Alternatively, UV photolysis of the thiol intermediate directly produces the dialdehyde through radical pathways, with H\u2082S acting as both reductant and sacrificial sulfur shuttle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanosulfidic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry; Sutherland group) demonstrates that H\u2082S participates in selective reductions and functional group interconversions under UV. Thiol-mediated conjugate additions to enones are highly favorable. UV-driven desulfurization producing reduced carbon products is established in cyanosulfidic networks. Sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) mediate these transformations (Islam & Powner, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidation of formaldehyde to glyoxylic acid on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild oxidation by pyrite surface S, pH ~6-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde first undergoes Cannizzaro disproportionation or Tischenko reaction at the pyrite surface: 2 HCHO \u2192 HCOOH + CH\u2083OH. Formic acid is then further oxidized. More directly, formaldehyde hydrate (methylene glycol) undergoes surface-catalyzed oxidation on pyrite to give glyoxylic acid via coupling of formate with CO\u2082: HCHO + CO\u2082 \u2192 glyoxylic acid under high-pressure hydrothermal conditions. Alternatively, formaldehyde oxidation yields formate, and two formate units couple on the mineral surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH) is among the simplest \u03b1-keto acids and a key prebiotic intermediate. Its formation from C1 species under hydrothermal conditions was reported by Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution). Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) identified glyoxylate as a central hub in non-enzymatic metabolic networks promoted by Fe\u00b2\u207a.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to 1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, rapid and spontaneous\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"One aldehyde of succinaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to a primary imine (Schiff base). The pendant aldehyde at C4 then undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the nitrogen, forming a 5-membered pyrrolidine ring. Dehydration of the resulting hemiaminal gives the cyclic imine 1-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This reaction is extremely fast (seconds to minutes) due to the thermodynamic favorability of 5-membered ring formation and is essentially quantitative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyclization of 1,4-dialdehydes with primary amines to form pyrroline is one of the most robust reactions in organic chemistry (Paal-Knorr type). Demonstrated prebiotically by Schlesinger & Miller (1983, J. Mol. Evol.) in the context of prebiotic amino acid synthesis. The reaction is spontaneous at room temperature and pH 7-9. Ring et al. (1972) detected 1-pyrroline as an intermediate in Miller-Urey experiments en route to proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker cyanation of 1-pyrroline to 2-cyanopyrrolidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"HCN at millimolar concentration, pH 7-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic carbon of the C=N imine bond in 1-pyrroline. The cyanide attacks from the less hindered face of the planar imine, producing 2-cyanopyrrolidine (\u03b1-aminonitrile). This is the classic Strecker addition applied to a cyclic imine. The reaction is kinetically controlled and occurs readily at ambient temperature with millimolar HCN. Montmorillonite surface adsorption can induce modest enantioselectivity (Hazen, 2001).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction on cyclic imines is the established mechanism for prebiotic proline synthesis (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983, J. Mol. Evol.; Ring et al., 1972, Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.). HCN addition to imines is one of the fastest and most efficient prebiotic reactions. 2-Cyanopyrrolidine was directly detected as an intermediate in spark discharge experiments. Chiral mineral surfaces can provide modest ee (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 2-cyanopyrrolidine to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling accelerates; mineral surfaces may catalyze\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two sequential hydrolysis steps: (1) 2-cyanopyrrolidine + H\u2082O \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide (amide intermediate), (2) pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide + H\u2082O \u2192 proline + NH\u2083. The nitrile hydrolysis is the rate-limiting step. Under mildly acidic conditions (pH 4-6) or upon heating, the nitrile is protonated, facilitating nucleophilic attack by water. The amide intermediate hydrolyzes more readily. Overall half-life at 80\u00b0C, pH 5 is hours to days.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide is the final step of the Strecker synthesis and is well-established for prebiotic amino acid formation (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The hydrolysis occurs under mild conditions and is accelerated by heat, acid, or mineral surfaces. This is the same mechanism by which all Strecker amino acids form in Miller-Urey experiments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde to aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"270-300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"low temperature favors kinetic trapping of open-chain aminonitrile over cyclization; high [HCN]/[NH\u2083] ratio >10 essential; reaction performed rapidly at 0-25\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under conditions of high HCN concentration and low temperature, the Strecker aminonitrile pathway competes kinetically with intramolecular cyclization. NH\u2083 adds to one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a carbinolamine; before cyclization can occur, HCN intercepts the nascent imine to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile. The remaining aldehyde group is preserved. The product is 2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile, a linear \u03b1-aminonitrile with a pendant aldehyde. This kinetic competition requires high [HCN] and low temperature to suppress the fast intramolecular cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The competition between Strecker cyanation and intramolecular cyclization in bifunctional substrates is discussed by Cleaves (2008, Precambrian Research). At high HCN concentrations, the Strecker pathway can outcompete cyclization because CN\u207b is a better nucleophile than an intramolecular amine. The open-chain aminonitrile has been proposed as an intermediate in glutamate semialdehyde formation (Weber, 2001). This is the more speculative of the two Strecker routes but provides an alternative entry to the P5C pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and cyclization of open-chain aminonitrile to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"warming triggers both nitrile hydrolysis and intramolecular cyclization; wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"At elevated temperature, the open-chain aminonitrile (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile) undergoes two concurrent processes: (1) nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate, producing glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA), and (2) spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA, where the \u03b1-amino group attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde to form the cyclic Schiff base \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) with loss of water. The cyclization is spontaneous and quantitative once GSA is formed.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is spontaneous and well-characterized biochemically (Adams & Frank, 1980, Biochem. J.). The key insight is that the open-chain Strecker aminonitrile provides a prebiotic route to GSA that avoids the problematic selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxylate group. Nitrile hydrolysis under warming/wet-dry conditions produces the acid, and the molecule immediately cyclizes. This circumvents the thermodynamic barrier identified in Attempt 1 feedback.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082S or formate as hydride donor; may also proceed via dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a as single-electron reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic imine (C=N) of P5C is reduced to the secondary amine of proline. H\u2082S serves as a mild, prebiotically abundant reducing agent: the sulfhydryl donates a hydride equivalent to the electrophilic imine carbon, producing the pyrrolidine ring and elemental sulfur. Alternatively, dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a can serve as an electron source in conjunction with proton donors. Formate-mediated transfer hydrogenation (HCOO\u207b \u2192 CO\u2082 + H\u207b) is also plausible. The resulting pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate is L-proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Imine reduction by H\u2082S is well-precedented in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry). H\u2082S is a mild and selective reducing agent for C=N bonds. Transfer hydrogenation by formate reducing imines has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Fe\u00b2\u207a-mediated reductions are supported by Keller et al. (2014). This step is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G\u00b0 \u2248 -30 kJ/mol for imine reduction).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylic acid to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with TiO\u2082\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, UV assists reductive step, mineral surface concentrates reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step one-pot transformation: (1) NH\u2083 attacks succinaldehyde at one aldehyde to form amino group, (2) the amino group undergoes transamination or reductive amination with glyoxylic acid's \u03b1-keto group to install the carboxylic acid functionality at the \u03b1-position, forming glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde in situ, (3) spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA gives P5C. The overall process combines ring closure with functionalization. TiO\u2082 UV photocatalysis assists the reductive amination step by generating reactive intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a fundamental prebiotic transformation (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). The coupling of succinaldehyde with glyoxylic acid to build a C5 \u03b1-amino acid framework is conceptually analogous to transamination reactions shown by Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) to occur non-enzymatically with Fe\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Montmorillonite surface concentration of reactants supports multi-component reactions (Ferris, 2005). This is a more speculative pathway but provides an alternative non-Strecker route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker synthesis of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde from succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"excess HCN, low temperature kinetic control as in rxn_014\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Identical mechanism to rxn_014 (open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde) followed by partial hydrolysis of the nitrile group to the carboxylic acid. Under prolonged aqueous conditions, the aminonitrile hydrolyzes to glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde directly. This reaction represents the combined rxn_014 + partial hydrolysis occurring in a single environment rather than sequential steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This combines the open-chain Strecker mechanism with in situ hydrolysis, representing the complete surface-environment route to GSA. The Strecker synthesis producing amino acids from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN is the best-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Applying it to one end of succinaldehyde while preserving the other aldehyde gives GSA directly.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"spontaneous, pH 5-8, extremely fast\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-amino group of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic addition to the \u03b3-aldehyde carbon, forming a carbinolamine. Dehydration produces the cyclic Schiff base \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This cyclization is spontaneous and essentially quantitative due to the thermodynamic stability of the 5-membered ring and the favorable entropy of intramolecular reaction. Equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic form (K_eq > 100).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is one of the best-characterized spontaneous intramolecular reactions in amino acid chemistry (Adams & Frank, 1980; Vogel & Davis, 1952). The reaction is so favorable that GSA has never been isolated in the open-chain form under physiological conditions. This spontaneous cyclization represents a reliable and essentially quantitative step in the network.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate\u2192Formaldehyde\u2192Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary hydrothermal-to-surface linear C1 buildup pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate, then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde transported to surface pools where formose chemistry builds glycolaldehyde, which self-condenses to erythrose. UV/TiO\u2082 photolysis converts erythrose to succinaldehyde. The dialdehyde cyclizes with NH\u2083 to 1-pyrroline, undergoes Strecker cyanation, and hydrolyzes to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde\u2192Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"The hydrothermal C3 route. CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite. Thermal decarboxylation on pyrite yields acetaldehyde. Transported to surface, acetaldehyde cross-condenses with glycolaldehyde to crotonaldehyde. H\u2082S/UV-mediated reductive hydration on stibnite converts crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde. Standard Strecker pathway completes proline synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Combined C1+C3: Formate\u2192Glycolaldehyde + Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde converge at Crotonaldehyde\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Convergent pathway using both hydrothermal branches. Formate branch supplies glycolaldehyde, pyruvate branch supplies acetaldehyde. These converge in the cross-aldol to crotonaldehyde on montmorillonite, then through cyanosulfidic reduction to succinaldehyde, cyclization, Strecker cyanation, and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Via the open-chain Strecker route. Succinaldehyde from erythrose photolysis reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN under kinetic control (low T, high [HCN]) to form open-chain aminonitrile. Warming triggers nitrile hydrolysis and spontaneous cyclization to P5C, which is reduced to proline by H\u2082S.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde-derived route through crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde, then kinetically controlled open-chain Strecker to bypass 1-pyrroline, forming the aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to GSA/P5C, reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde + Glyoxylic acid reductive amination\u2192P5C\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Non-Strecker route via glyoxylic acid. Glyoxylic acid formed from formaldehyde oxidation in hydrothermal vents. Succinaldehyde (from either erythrose or crotonaldehyde route) reacts with glyoxylic acid and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite/TiO\u2082 to form P5C directly. P5C is reduced to proline by H\u2082S.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-derived succinaldehyde + glyoxylic acid\u2192P5C\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant of P6 using acetaldehyde/crotonaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde instead of erythrose-derived. Combines the pyruvate decarboxylation branch with glyoxylic acid to construct P5C.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct GSA synthesis from succinaldehyde Strecker\u2192cyclization\u2192reduction\",\n      \"description\": \"One-pot surface Strecker on succinaldehyde at low temperature yields GSA directly upon hydrolysis. GSA spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, reduced to proline. Uses erythrose-derived succinaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Crotonaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines the acetaldehyde cross-aldol route to succinaldehyde with the surface Strecker route to GSA. Crotonaldehyde-to-succinaldehyde via H\u2082S cyanosulfidic chemistry, then open-chain Strecker at low temperature to GSA, cyclization to P5C, reduction to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal Strecker: Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde+Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest credible route combining pyruvate-derived formaldehyde (via the formate branch) with glycolaldehyde\u2192erythrose formose chemistry. Erythrose UV-photolysis to succinaldehyde, cyclization to 1-pyrroline, Strecker cyanation and hydrolysis to proline. This pathway demonstrates full environmental interconnection: hydrothermal C-fixation \u2192 surface photochemistry and formose \u2192 biochemical hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_020\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - central C1 hub from hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction, feeds formose chemistry, glyoxylate synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde - C2 sugar hub from formose reaction, feeds erythrose synthesis and cross-aldol with acetaldehyde\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde - C2 hub from pyruvate decarboxylation, feeds cross-aldol condensation to crotonaldehyde\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Succinaldehyde - critical C4 convergence node. Formed from erythrose photolysis OR crotonaldehyde reductive hydration. Feeds 1-pyrroline cyclization, open-chain Strecker, GSA Strecker, and reductive amination with glyoxylic acid. The most connected hub in the network (degree 7).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C (\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate) - penultimate precursor to proline via imine reduction. Formed from three distinct routes: open-chain aminonitrile hydrolysis/cyclization, reductive amination with glyoxylic acid, or GSA cyclization.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "Two convergent branches supply C1-C4 building blocks to the critical hub molecule succinaldehyde via distinct routes: (A) a hydrothermal CO\u2082-fixation branch producing formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192erythrose\u2192succinaldehyde, and (B) a hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation branch producing acetaldehyde that cross-condenses with glycolaldehyde to yield succinaldehyde. Succinaldehyde undergoes rapid intramolecular cyclization with NH\u2083 to form 1-pyrroline, which then enters a Strecker cyanation/hydrolysis sequence to give proline. An alternative direct hydrothermal reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylate provides a non-Strecker route. A separate surface Strecker route via glutamate semialdehyde provides a biologically-inspired pathway through P5C. All mineral catalysts are explicitly specified. Enantioselection arises from adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Hazen, 2001) and chiral amplification during wet-dry cycling on montmorillonite (Ferris et al., 1996). 10 distinct end-to-end pathways traverse the network through 5 hub molecules.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H8O3", "iupac_name": "(2R,3R)-2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal", "common_name": "D-erythrose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h1,3-4,6-8H,2H2/t3-,4-/m1/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H7N", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "1-pyrroline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "2-cyanopyrrolidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "(E)-but-2-enal", "common_name": "crotonaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O/c1-2-3-4-5/h2-4H,1H3/b3-2+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(S)-5-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "5-aminolevulinate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8-9/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C2HNO2", "iupac_name": "oxo(hydroxy)acetonitrile", "common_name": "cyanohydrin of glyoxylate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C5H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile", "common_name": "open-chain Strecker aminonitrile of succinaldehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on greigite surface Fe sites, undergoes two-electron reduction by H\u2082 via surface-bound hydride intermediates. Greigite serves as structural/electronic analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] ferredoxin clusters. Formate is released as the primary C1 product.", "reasoning": "Experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed native metals and Fe\u2083S\u2084 from hydrothermal precipitates reduce CO\u2082 to formate at 100\u00b0C under modest H\u2082 pressures. Also supported by Roldan et al. (2015, Chem. Commun.) who showed greigite electrocatalytically reduces CO\u2082 to formate. Yields of ~50-200 \u00b5M formate observed."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["native iron (Fe\u2070)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-450K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe\u2070) with magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "reducing conditions, Eh < -0.5V"}, "mechanism": "Formate undergoes further two-electron reduction on Fe\u2070 surface to formaldehyde via surface-bound formyl intermediate. Fe\u2070 is oxidized to Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u2083O\u2084. Highly reducing conditions required due to the thermodynamic difficulty of formate\u2192formaldehyde reduction (\u0394G\u00b0 \u2248 +24 kJ/mol at standard state but favored at high H\u2082 pressures).", "reasoning": "He et al. (2019, PNAS) demonstrated stepwise CO\u2082 reduction through formate to formaldehyde on native iron under hydrothermal conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) showed Ni\u2070 and Fe\u2070 from serpentinization can drive this chemistry. Formaldehyde is unstable and rapidly undergoes Cannizzaro reaction or polymerization, so steady-state concentrations are low but sufficient for downstream chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite with greigite co-catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox cycling"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO\u2082 reduction and C-C coupling on mineral surfaces. CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate via surface-catalyzed condensation and oxidation steps. The overall process involves multiple surface-bound intermediates but pyruvate accumulates as a thermodynamic sink among C3 products. Mineral surface templating directs selectivity toward \u03b1-keto acids.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, J. Am. Chem. Soc.) demonstrated formation of pyruvate from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on iron-containing minerals. Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) showed Fe(OH)\u2082 promotes CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate and other organic acids under mild hydrothermal conditions. Pyruvate yields are low (\u00b5M) but it is a key metabolic hub molecule with demonstrated prebiotic formation."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "non-oxidative decarboxylation, slightly acidic conditions at vent wall"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal non-oxidative decarboxylation on pyrite surface. The \u03b1-keto acid is activated by surface Fe\u00b2\u207a coordination to both carbonyl and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the decarboxylation barrier. CO\u2082 is lost and acetaldehyde released. This is one of the most facile thermal reactions of pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is well-established at hydrothermal temperatures (Cody et al., 2000, Science; Seewald et al., 2006, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta). Half-life of pyruvate at 250\u00b0C is minutes. FeS\u2082 surfaces accelerate the reaction. Acetaldehyde is the sole organic product, making this a clean and high-yield transformation."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with Ca(OH)\u2082 and borate", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline solution, pH 10-11, trace glycolaldehyde as autocatalyst"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed formose reaction. Formaldehyde undergoes Cannizzaro-type umpolung: one HCHO molecule acts as nucleophile (via enolization/carbanion) and attacks another. Ca\u00b2\u207a ions from Ca(OH)\u2082 catalyze the initial dimerization. Borate complexation selectively stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further polymerization by forming cyclic borate esters, channeling the formose reaction toward C2 products.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is the classic prebiotic sugar synthesis (Butlerow, 1861). Borate stabilization of specific sugar intermediates was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) and Benner et al. (2012). Montmorillonite surfaces template the reaction and reduce the diversity of products (Gabel & Ponnamperuma, 1967). Glycolaldehyde is the first stable C2 product."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "borate minerals (ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with borate", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline conditions pH ~10, borate stabilizes tetrose product"}, "mechanism": "Self-aldol condensation of two glycolaldehyde molecules. One glycolaldehyde enolizes at the \u03b1-carbon (catalyzed by base/clay surface); the resulting enolate attacks the aldehyde of a second glycolaldehyde molecule. The aldol product is erythrose (threo/erythro mixture). Borate minerals form cyclic 1,2-diol esters with erythrose, stabilizing it against retro-aldol and further aldol reactions.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde self-aldol to tetroses is a well-characterized step in the formose network (Breslow, 1959; Orgel, 2000). Borate stabilization of sugar intermediates selects for specific products (Ricardo et al., 2004, Science). Kim et al. (2011) showed montmorillonite catalyzes aldol condensations of small aldehydes. Erythrose yields of 5-15% achievable."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photodegradation of erythrose to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "TiO\u2082-photocatalyzed dehydration and reduction of erythrose. UV excitation of TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs; the holes oxidize the hydroxyl groups of erythrose while electrons reduce intermediates. Sequential loss of two hydroxyl groups as water converts erythrose (HOCH\u2082CHOHCHOHCHO, C\u2084H\u2088O\u2084) to succinaldehyde (OHCCH\u2082CH\u2082CHO, C\u2084H\u2086O\u2082). This represents a net 2-electron reduction with loss of 2H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 serves as both UV absorber and redox mediator.", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082 photocatalysis of sugar decomposition and rearrangement is well documented (Chong et al., 2010). UV photolysis of sugars producing dialdehydes and other carbonyl compounds was demonstrated by Zhu et al. (2020). The conversion of polyols to dialdehydes via UV/TiO\u2082 is thermodynamically favorable under UV irradiation. On early Earth, intense UV (no ozone shield) and abundant TiO\u2082 mineral surfaces made this pathway accessible (Sasselov et al., 2020, Science Advances)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde via crotonaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with phosphate surface sites", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline pH 8-9, mineral surface templating"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde enolizes on the montmorillonite clay surface (base-catalyzed by surface siloxide groups). The acetaldehyde enolate attacks the aldehyde of glycolaldehyde to form a \u03b2-hydroxycarbonyl C4 intermediate (4-hydroxy-3-oxobutanal), which readily undergoes elimination of water (driven by conjugation) to produce the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde crotonaldehyde (2-butenal). Phosphate surface sites stabilize the transition state for elimination.", "reasoning": "Cross-aldol condensations between small aldehydes are among the most facile prebiotic reactions on mineral surfaces. Montmorillonite-catalyzed aldol condensations demonstrated by Gabel & Ponnamperuma (1967). Crotonaldehyde formation from acetaldehyde under mild basic conditions is well known in organic chemistry and represents a thermodynamic product (Weber, 2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive hydration of crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, Sb\u2082S\u2083)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "stibnite and montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082S as reductant, UV exposure, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Crotonaldehyde (CH\u2083CH=CHCHO) undergoes conjugate (1,4-) addition of H\u2082S to form 3-(sulfanyl)butanal. Subsequent UV-driven desulfurization on sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) and hydrolysis cleaves the C-S bond with net reduction of the C=C double bond and oxidation of the terminal methyl to aldehyde. The overall transformation is: CH\u2083CH=CHCHO + H\u2082S + [O] \u2192 OHCCH\u2082CH\u2082CHO + H\u2082S. Alternatively, UV photolysis of the thiol intermediate directly produces the dialdehyde through radical pathways, with H\u2082S acting as both reductant and sacrificial sulfur shuttle.", "reasoning": "Cyanosulfidic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry; Sutherland group) demonstrates that H\u2082S participates in selective reductions and functional group interconversions under UV. Thiol-mediated conjugate additions to enones are highly favorable. UV-driven desulfurization producing reduced carbon products is established in cyanosulfidic networks. Sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) mediate these transformations (Islam & Powner, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Oxidation of formaldehyde to glyoxylic acid on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild oxidation by pyrite surface S, pH ~6-8"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde first undergoes Cannizzaro disproportionation or Tischenko reaction at the pyrite surface: 2 HCHO \u2192 HCOOH + CH\u2083OH. Formic acid is then further oxidized. More directly, formaldehyde hydrate (methylene glycol) undergoes surface-catalyzed oxidation on pyrite to give glyoxylic acid via coupling of formate with CO\u2082: HCHO + CO\u2082 \u2192 glyoxylic acid under high-pressure hydrothermal conditions. Alternatively, formaldehyde oxidation yields formate, and two formate units couple on the mineral surface.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH) is among the simplest \u03b1-keto acids and a key prebiotic intermediate. Its formation from C1 species under hydrothermal conditions was reported by Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution). Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) identified glyoxylate as a central hub in non-enzymatic metabolic networks promoted by Fe\u00b2\u207a."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to 1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, rapid and spontaneous"}, "mechanism": "One aldehyde of succinaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to a primary imine (Schiff base). The pendant aldehyde at C4 then undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the nitrogen, forming a 5-membered pyrrolidine ring. Dehydration of the resulting hemiaminal gives the cyclic imine 1-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This reaction is extremely fast (seconds to minutes) due to the thermodynamic favorability of 5-membered ring formation and is essentially quantitative.", "reasoning": "The cyclization of 1,4-dialdehydes with primary amines to form pyrroline is one of the most robust reactions in organic chemistry (Paal-Knorr type). Demonstrated prebiotically by Schlesinger & Miller (1983, J. Mol. Evol.) in the context of prebiotic amino acid synthesis. The reaction is spontaneous at room temperature and pH 7-9. Ring et al. (1972) detected 1-pyrroline as an intermediate in Miller-Urey experiments en route to proline."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Strecker cyanation of 1-pyrroline to 2-cyanopyrrolidine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "HCN at millimolar concentration, pH 7-9"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic carbon of the C=N imine bond in 1-pyrroline. The cyanide attacks from the less hindered face of the planar imine, producing 2-cyanopyrrolidine (\u03b1-aminonitrile). This is the classic Strecker addition applied to a cyclic imine. The reaction is kinetically controlled and occurs readily at ambient temperature with millimolar HCN. Montmorillonite surface adsorption can induce modest enantioselectivity (Hazen, 2001).", "reasoning": "The Strecker reaction on cyclic imines is the established mechanism for prebiotic proline synthesis (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983, J. Mol. Evol.; Ring et al., 1972, Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.). HCN addition to imines is one of the fastest and most efficient prebiotic reactions. 2-Cyanopyrrolidine was directly detected as an intermediate in spark discharge experiments. Chiral mineral surfaces can provide modest ee (Hazen et al., 2001, PNAS)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of 2-cyanopyrrolidine to proline", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling accelerates; mineral surfaces may catalyze"}, "mechanism": "Two sequential hydrolysis steps: (1) 2-cyanopyrrolidine + H\u2082O \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide (amide intermediate), (2) pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide + H\u2082O \u2192 proline + NH\u2083. The nitrile hydrolysis is the rate-limiting step. Under mildly acidic conditions (pH 4-6) or upon heating, the nitrile is protonated, facilitating nucleophilic attack by water. The amide intermediate hydrolyzes more readily. Overall half-life at 80\u00b0C, pH 5 is hours to days.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide is the final step of the Strecker synthesis and is well-established for prebiotic amino acid formation (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The hydrolysis occurs under mild conditions and is accelerated by heat, acid, or mineral surfaces. This is the same mechanism by which all Strecker amino acids form in Miller-Urey experiments."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde to aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "270-300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "low temperature favors kinetic trapping of open-chain aminonitrile over cyclization; high [HCN]/[NH\u2083] ratio >10 essential; reaction performed rapidly at 0-25\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "Under conditions of high HCN concentration and low temperature, the Strecker aminonitrile pathway competes kinetically with intramolecular cyclization. NH\u2083 adds to one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a carbinolamine; before cyclization can occur, HCN intercepts the nascent imine to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile. The remaining aldehyde group is preserved. The product is 2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile, a linear \u03b1-aminonitrile with a pendant aldehyde. This kinetic competition requires high [HCN] and low temperature to suppress the fast intramolecular cyclization.", "reasoning": "The competition between Strecker cyanation and intramolecular cyclization in bifunctional substrates is discussed by Cleaves (2008, Precambrian Research). At high HCN concentrations, the Strecker pathway can outcompete cyclization because CN\u207b is a better nucleophile than an intramolecular amine. The open-chain aminonitrile has been proposed as an intermediate in glutamate semialdehyde formation (Weber, 2001). This is the more speculative of the two Strecker routes but provides an alternative entry to the P5C pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolysis and cyclization of open-chain aminonitrile to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_023", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "warming triggers both nitrile hydrolysis and intramolecular cyclization; wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "At elevated temperature, the open-chain aminonitrile (2-amino-5-oxopentanenitrile) undergoes two concurrent processes: (1) nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate, producing glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA), and (2) spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA, where the \u03b1-amino group attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde to form the cyclic Schiff base \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) with loss of water. The cyclization is spontaneous and quantitative once GSA is formed.", "reasoning": "GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is spontaneous and well-characterized biochemically (Adams & Frank, 1980, Biochem. J.). The key insight is that the open-chain Strecker aminonitrile provides a prebiotic route to GSA that avoids the problematic selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxylate group. Nitrile hydrolysis under warming/wet-dry conditions produces the acid, and the molecule immediately cyclizes. This circumvents the thermodynamic barrier identified in Attempt 1 feedback."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Reduction of P5C to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082S or formate as hydride donor; may also proceed via dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a as single-electron reductant"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic imine (C=N) of P5C is reduced to the secondary amine of proline. H\u2082S serves as a mild, prebiotically abundant reducing agent: the sulfhydryl donates a hydride equivalent to the electrophilic imine carbon, producing the pyrrolidine ring and elemental sulfur. Alternatively, dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a can serve as an electron source in conjunction with proton donors. Formate-mediated transfer hydrogenation (HCOO\u207b \u2192 CO\u2082 + H\u207b) is also plausible. The resulting pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate is L-proline.", "reasoning": "Imine reduction by H\u2082S is well-precedented in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry). H\u2082S is a mild and selective reducing agent for C=N bonds. Transfer hydrogenation by formate reducing imines has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Fe\u00b2\u207a-mediated reductions are supported by Keller et al. (2014). This step is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G\u00b0 \u2248 -30 kJ/mol for imine reduction)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylic acid to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_022", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with TiO\u2082", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, UV assists reductive step, mineral surface concentrates reactants"}, "mechanism": "Multi-step one-pot transformation: (1) NH\u2083 attacks succinaldehyde at one aldehyde to form amino group, (2) the amino group undergoes transamination or reductive amination with glyoxylic acid's \u03b1-keto group to install the carboxylic acid functionality at the \u03b1-position, forming glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde in situ, (3) spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA gives P5C. The overall process combines ring closure with functionalization. TiO\u2082 UV photocatalysis assists the reductive amination step by generating reactive intermediates.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a fundamental prebiotic transformation (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). The coupling of succinaldehyde with glyoxylic acid to build a C5 \u03b1-amino acid framework is conceptually analogous to transamination reactions shown by Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) to occur non-enzymatically with Fe\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Montmorillonite surface concentration of reactants supports multi-component reactions (Ferris, 2005). This is a more speculative pathway but provides an alternative non-Strecker route."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde from succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "excess HCN, low temperature kinetic control as in rxn_014"}, "mechanism": "Identical mechanism to rxn_014 (open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde) followed by partial hydrolysis of the nitrile group to the carboxylic acid. Under prolonged aqueous conditions, the aminonitrile hydrolyzes to glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde directly. This reaction represents the combined rxn_014 + partial hydrolysis occurring in a single environment rather than sequential steps.", "reasoning": "This combines the open-chain Strecker mechanism with in situ hydrolysis, representing the complete surface-environment route to GSA. The Strecker synthesis producing amino acids from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN is the best-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Applying it to one end of succinaldehyde while preserving the other aldehyde gives GSA directly."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "spontaneous, pH 5-8, extremely fast"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-amino group of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic addition to the \u03b3-aldehyde carbon, forming a carbinolamine. Dehydration produces the cyclic Schiff base \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This cyclization is spontaneous and essentially quantitative due to the thermodynamic stability of the 5-membered ring and the favorable entropy of intramolecular reaction. Equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic form (K_eq > 100).", "reasoning": "GSA\u2192P5C cyclization is one of the best-characterized spontaneous intramolecular reactions in amino acid chemistry (Adams & Frank, 1980; Vogel & Davis, 1952). The reaction is so favorable that GSA has never been isolated in the open-chain form under physiological conditions. This spontaneous cyclization represents a reliable and essentially quantitative step in the network."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Formate\u2192Formaldehyde\u2192Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline", "description": "The primary hydrothermal-to-surface linear C1 buildup pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate, then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde transported to surface pools where formose chemistry builds glycolaldehyde, which self-condenses to erythrose. UV/TiO\u2082 photolysis converts erythrose to succinaldehyde. The dialdehyde cyclizes with NH\u2083 to 1-pyrroline, undergoes Strecker cyanation, and hydrolyzes to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde\u2192Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline", "description": "The hydrothermal C3 route. CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite. Thermal decarboxylation on pyrite yields acetaldehyde. Transported to surface, acetaldehyde cross-condenses with glycolaldehyde to crotonaldehyde. H\u2082S/UV-mediated reductive hydration on stibnite converts crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde. Standard Strecker pathway completes proline synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_017", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Combined C1+C3: Formate\u2192Glycolaldehyde + Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde converge at Crotonaldehyde\u2192Proline", "description": "Convergent pathway using both hydrothermal branches. Formate branch supplies glycolaldehyde, pyruvate branch supplies acetaldehyde. These converge in the cross-aldol to crotonaldehyde on montmorillonite, then through cyanosulfidic reduction to succinaldehyde, cyclization, Strecker cyanation, and hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_017", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline", "description": "Via the open-chain Strecker route. Succinaldehyde from erythrose photolysis reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN under kinetic control (low T, high [HCN]) to form open-chain aminonitrile. Warming triggers nitrile hydrolysis and spontaneous cyclization to P5C, which is reduced to proline by H\u2082S.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_023", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline", "description": "Acetaldehyde-derived route through crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde, then kinetically controlled open-chain Strecker to bypass 1-pyrroline, forming the aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to GSA/P5C, reduced to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_017", "mol_013", "mol_023", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Succinaldehyde + Glyoxylic acid reductive amination\u2192P5C\u2192Proline", "description": "Non-Strecker route via glyoxylic acid. Glyoxylic acid formed from formaldehyde oxidation in hydrothermal vents. Succinaldehyde (from either erythrose or crotonaldehyde route) reacts with glyoxylic acid and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite/TiO\u2082 to form P5C directly. P5C is reduced to proline by H\u2082S.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_010", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_022", "mol_013", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Pyruvate-derived succinaldehyde + glyoxylic acid\u2192P5C\u2192Proline", "description": "Variant of P6 using acetaldehyde/crotonaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde instead of erythrose-derived. Combines the pyruvate decarboxylation branch with glyoxylic acid to construct P5C.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_017", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_022", "mol_017", "mol_013", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Direct GSA synthesis from succinaldehyde Strecker\u2192cyclization\u2192reduction", "description": "One-pot surface Strecker on succinaldehyde at low temperature yields GSA directly upon hydrolysis. GSA spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, reduced to proline. Uses erythrose-derived succinaldehyde.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Crotonaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192Proline", "description": "Combines the acetaldehyde cross-aldol route to succinaldehyde with the surface Strecker route to GSA. Crotonaldehyde-to-succinaldehyde via H\u2082S cyanosulfidic chemistry, then open-chain Strecker at low temperature to GSA, cyclization to P5C, reduction to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_013", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Minimal Strecker: Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde+Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Proline", "description": "Shortest credible route combining pyruvate-derived formaldehyde (via the formate branch) with glycolaldehyde\u2192erythrose formose chemistry. Erythrose UV-photolysis to succinaldehyde, cyclization to 1-pyrroline, Strecker cyanation and hydrolysis to proline. This pathway demonstrates full environmental interconnection: hydrothermal C-fixation \u2192 surface photochemistry and formose \u2192 biochemical hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_020"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde - central C1 hub from hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction, feeds formose chemistry, glyoxylate synthesis", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Glycolaldehyde - C2 sugar hub from formose reaction, feeds erythrose synthesis and cross-aldol with acetaldehyde", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Acetaldehyde - C2 hub from pyruvate decarboxylation, feeds cross-aldol condensation to crotonaldehyde", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Succinaldehyde - critical C4 convergence node. Formed from erythrose photolysis OR crotonaldehyde reductive hydration. Feeds 1-pyrroline cyclization, open-chain Strecker, GSA Strecker, and reductive amination with glyoxylic acid. The most connected hub in the network (degree 7).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_014", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_020", "description": "P5C (\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate) - penultimate precursor to proline via imine reduction. Formed from three distinct routes: open-chain aminonitrile hydrolysis/cyclization, reductive amination with glyoxylic acid, or GSA cyclization.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_016"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 520174.86906051636, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T10:43:13.364459", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Proline\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Two convergent branches supply C1-C4 building blocks to the critical hub molecule succinaldehyde via distinct routes: (A) a hydrothermal CO\u2082-fixation branch producing formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192erythrose\u2192succinaldehyde, and (B) a hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation branch producing acetaldehyde that cross-condenses with glycolaldehyde to yield succinaldehyde. Succinaldehyde undergoes rapid intramolecular cyclization with NH\u2083 to form 1-pyrroline, which then enters a Strecker cyanation/hydrolysis sequence to give proline. An alternative direct hydrothermal reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylate provides a non-Strecker route. A separate surface Strecker route via glutamate semialdehyde provides a biologically-inspired pathway through P5C. All mineral catalysts are explicitly specified. Enantioselection arises from adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Hazen, 2001) and chiral amplification during wet-dry cycling on montmorillonite (Ferris et al., 1996). 10 distinct end-to-end pathways traverse the network through 5 hub molecules.\n\nMOLECULES (23 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CHOO- (formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H8O3 (D-erythrose) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H6O2 (succinaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H7N (1-pyrroline) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C5H8N2 (2-cyanopyrrolidine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H9NO2 (L-proline) [target]\n  - mol_017: C4H6O2 (crotonaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C5H9NO3 (5-aminolevulinate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C5H9NO3 (glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_020: C5H7NO2 (L-\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: C2HNO2 (cyanohydrin of glyoxylate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_022: C2H2O3 (glyoxylic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_023: C5H8N2O (open-chain Strecker aminonitrile of succinaldehyde) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (19 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_008, mol_005 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_010 (CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_010 -> mol_011, mol_001 (Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_008 -> mol_009 (Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_009 -> mol_012 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_012 -> mol_013, mol_005 (UV photodegradation of erythrose to succinaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_011 -> mol_017, mol_005 (Cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde via crotonaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_017, mol_006 -> mol_013 (Reductive hydration of crotonaldehyde to succinaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_008, mol_005 -> mol_022 (Oxidation of formaldehyde to glyoxylic acid on pyrite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_013, mol_003 -> mol_014, mol_005 (Intramolecular cyclization of succinaldehyde with ammonia to 1-pyrroline) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_014, mol_004 -> mol_015 (Strecker cyanation of 1-pyrroline to 2-cyanopyrrolidine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_015, mol_005 -> mol_016, mol_003 (Hydrolysis of 2-cyanopyrrolidine to proline) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_014: mol_013, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_023 (Open-chain Strecker on succinaldehyde to aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_023, mol_005 -> mol_020, mol_003 (Hydrolysis and cyclization of open-chain aminonitrile to P5C) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_020, mol_006 -> mol_016 (Reduction of P5C to L-proline) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_017: mol_013, mol_022, mol_003 -> mol_020, mol_005 (Reductive amination of succinaldehyde with glyoxylic acid to P5C) [Surface]\n  - rxn_018: mol_013, mol_003, mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_019 (Direct Strecker synthesis of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde from succinaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_019: mol_019 -> mol_020, mol_005 (Spontaneous cyclization of glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Formate\u2192Formaldehyde\u2192Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline (8 steps)\n  - P2: Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde\u2192Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192Proline (7 steps)\n  - P3: Combined C1+C3: Formate\u2192Glycolaldehyde + Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde converge at Crotonaldehyde\u2192Proline (10 steps)\n  - P4: Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline (8 steps)\n  - P5: Crotonaldehyde\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Open-chain Strecker\u2192P5C\u2192Proline (7 steps)\n  - P6: Succinaldehyde + Glyoxylic acid reductive amination\u2192P5C\u2192Proline (8 steps)\n  - P7: Pyruvate-derived succinaldehyde + glyoxylic acid\u2192P5C\u2192Proline (10 steps)\n  - P8: Direct GSA synthesis from succinaldehyde Strecker\u2192cyclization\u2192reduction (8 steps)\n  - P9: Crotonaldehyde-derived succinaldehyde\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192Proline (10 steps)\n  - P10: Minimal Strecker: Pyruvate\u2192Acetaldehyde+Glycolaldehyde\u2192Erythrose\u2192Succinaldehyde\u2192Pyrroline\u2192Proline (8 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_008, mol_009, mol_011, mol_013, mol_020\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.74,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"The strongest linear pathway. The C1 assembly to succinaldehyde is creative but rxn_007 (UV photodegradation of erythrose to succinaldehyde) is the weakest link: erythrose (C4H8O4) to succinaldehyde (C4H6O2) requires loss of two oxygens and UV photolysis alone is unlikely to achieve selective double deoxygenation. rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde) is thermodynamically uphill and the yield would be very low. The downstream succinaldehyde\u2192pyrroline\u2192Strecker\u2192proline segment is well-supported.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_002\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace rxn_007 with a more plausible route: consider retro-aldol of erythrose to two glycolaldehyde units followed by selective reduction, or use a different C4 dialdehyde source.\",\n        \"Specify mineral catalyst for rxn_005 and rxn_006 (e.g., borate minerals for formose selectivity).\",\n        \"Consider alternative formaldehyde sources (e.g., serpentinization-derived CH2O) to bypass rxn_002.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.55,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.58,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n      \"feedback\": \"rxn_008 is mis-specified: the cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) with acetaldehyde would not yield crotonaldehyde (CH3CH=CHCHO), which is the self-aldol condensation product of acetaldehyde alone. rxn_009 is stoichiometrically and mechanistically implausible: converting crotonaldehyde (C4H6O) to succinaldehyde (C4H6O2) requires net oxidation at the methyl terminus, but H2S is a reductant. The pathway also implicitly requires glycolaldehyde from the C1 branch, so it is not independent.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Correct rxn_008: if acetaldehyde self-condenses to crotonaldehyde, use only acetaldehyde as input. Otherwise, model the true cross-aldol product.\",\n        \"Replace rxn_009 with a plausible transformation, e.g., ozonolysis or radical oxidation of the terminal methyl, or find a